y:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:2. Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Sweden youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2016 players]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = John Guidetti\n|image          = John Guidetti 2017 (cropped).jpg\n|image_size = 200\n|caption        = Guidetti playing for [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] in 2017\n|fullname       = John Alberto Guidetti<ref>{{cite web |url=http://actas.rfef.es/actas/RFEF_CmpActa1?cod_primaria=1000144&CodActa=57339 |title=Acta del Partido celebrado el 18 de mayo de 2019, en Vitoria-Gasteiz |trans-title=Minutes of the Match held on 18 May 2019, in Vitoria-Gasteiz |publisher=Royal Spanish Football Federation |accessdate=16 June 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1992|4|15|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n|height         = 1.85 m<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tournament.fifadata.com/documents/FWC/2018/pdf/FWC_2018_SQUADLISTS.PDF |title=2018 FIFA World Cup Russia \u2013 List of Players |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |date=4 June 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018}}</ref>\n|position       = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n|currentclub    = [[Hannover 96]]<br>(on loan from [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]])\n|clubnumber     = 9\n|youthyears1    = 1998\u20132002 |youthclubs1 = [[IF Brommapojkarna]]\n|youthyears2    = 2002\u20132003 |youthclubs2 = Impala BrommaBoys\n|youthyears3    = 2003\u20132004 |youthclubs3 = [[Mathare United F.C.|Mathare United]]\n|youthyears4    = 2004\u20132005 |youthclubs4 = [[Ligi Ndogo S.C.|Ligi Ndogo]]\n|youthyears5    = 2006\u20132008 |youthclubs5 = [[IF Brommapojkarna]]\n|years1         = 2008      | clubs1 = [[IF Brommapojkarna]]                     | caps1 = 2  | goals1 = 0\n|years2         = 2008\u20132015 | clubs2 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]  | caps2 = 0  | goals2 = 0\n|years3         = 2010      | clubs3 = \u2192 [[IF Brommapojkarna]]  (loan)           | caps3 = 8  | goals3 = 3\n|years4         = 2010\u20132011 | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] (loan)         | caps4 = 4  | goals4 = 1\n|years5         = 2011\u20132012 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Feyenoord]] (loan)                    | caps5 = 23 | goals5 = 20\n|years6         = 2014      | clubs6 = \u2192 [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] (loan)   | caps6 = 6  | goals6 = 0\n|years7         = 2014\u20132015 | clubs7 = \u2192 [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] (loan)           | caps7 = 24 | goals7 = 8\n|years8         = 2015\u20132018 | clubs8 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]]                | caps8 = 66 | goals8 = 11\n|years9         = 2018     | clubs9 =  \u2192 [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]] (loan)      | caps9 = 17 | goals9 = 3\n|years10         = 2018\u2013     | clubs10 =  [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]]            | caps10 = 27 | goals10 = 2\n|years11         = 2020\u2013     | clubs11 =  \u2192 [[Hannover 96]] (loan)                | caps11 = 0 | goals11 = 0\n|nationalyears1 = 2007\u20132009 |nationalteam1 = [[Sweden national under-17 football team|Sweden U17]] |nationalcaps1 = 11 |nationalgoals1 = 8\n|nationalyears2 = 2009\u20132010 |nationalteam2 = [[Sweden national under-19 football team|Sweden U19]] |nationalcaps2 = 5  |nationalgoals2 = 5\n|nationalyears3 = 2010\u20132015 |nationalteam3 = [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden U21]] |nationalcaps3 = 23 |nationalgoals3 = 12\n|nationalyears4 = 2012\u2013     |nationalteam4 = [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]              |nationalcaps4 = 28 |nationalgoals4 = 3\n|club-update = 17 January 2020\n|nationalteam-update = 18 November 2019\n}}\n'''John Alberto Guidetti''' ({{IPA-sv|\u0261\u0275\u02c8d\u025b\u030ct\u02d0\u026a, \u0261\u026a-|lang}},<ref>https://forvo.com/word/john_guidetti/#sv</ref> {{IPA-it|\u0261wi\u02c8detti|lang}};<ref>https://forvo.com/word/guidetti/</ref> born 15 April 1992) is a Swedish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] for German club [[Hannover 96]], on loan from Spanish club [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s]].\n\nWhilst growing up Guidetti played football in his native Sweden as well as [[Kenya]]. He returned to Sweden in 2008 and played with [[IF Brommapojkarna]] when at the age of 16 he earned a move to English club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. He spent time out on loan back at Brommapojkarna and with Championship side [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] in November 2010. He joined Dutch club [[Feyenoord]] on loan for the [[Eredivisie 2011-12|2011\u201312]] season where he scored 20 goals in 23 games before a virus ended his time in the Netherlands. In January 2014, Guidetti joined [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on loan until the end of the [[2013\u201314 Stoke City F.C. season|2013\u201314]] season, and in September of that year he was loaned to Scottish champions [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] for the following season, winning the [[Scottish Premiership]] and [[Scottish League Cup]]. In July 2015, Guidetti signed for Spanish side [[Celta de Vigo|Celta]].\nHaving represented Sweden at several youth levels, he earned his first senior international cap against Croatia on 29 February 2012. At [[Sweden national under-21 football team|under-21 level]], he won the [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2015 European Championship]]. He represented Sweden's [[Sweden national football team|senior team]] at [[Euro 2016]] and at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=\"goal.com\">http://www.goal.com/en-kw/news/ekdal-included-in-swedens-euro-2016-squad/o6pojxiyz3ar10x5cdatk4nv5</ref><ref>https://indianexpress.com/article/fifa/fifa-world-cup-2018-kenya-is-cheering-for-sweden-against-england-and-john-guidetti-is-the-main-reason-5249244/</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nGuidetti began his football career at the [[Sweden|Swedish]] club [[IF Brommapojkarna]]'s youth system in 1998. In 2002, Guidetti moved with his family to [[Kenya]], as his father had a job there. This meant that Guidetti had to leave BP, and he joined the Impala BrommaBoys [[Youth system|football academy]] based in [[Nairobi]].\n\nAfter one year with the Impala club, Guidetti joined [[Mathare United F.C.|Mathare United]]'s academy, the MYSA organisation for sports [[development aid]], in the [[slums]] of [[Nairobi]]. In 2004, Guidetti left the organisation and joined [[Ligi Ndogo S.C.|Ligi Ndogo]]. In 2006, he returned to Sweden with [[IF Brommapojkarna]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ligi Ndogo player signed by Manchester City |url=http://www.kenyafootball.com/index.php?doc=story&id=2908&categ=1 |publisher=KenyaFootball.com |date=28 August 2008 |accessdate=30 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425133151/http://www.kenyafootball.com/index.php?doc=story&id=2908&categ=1 |archivedate=25 April 2012  }}</ref> In total Guidetti spent around five years living in Kenya which he states helped him to develop on and off the pitch:\n\n{{Quote|That period was very important for my development, both on and off the pitch. I played football barefoot in the slum areas of Nairobi and I came into contact with local people and their culture. I still have a strong link with Kenya and every time I go back there I always get a warm welcome.|Guidetti on his time living in Kenya.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sensational John Guidetti Firing Feyenoord Forward|url=http://www.insidefutbol.com/2012/03/07/sensational-john-guidetti-firing-feyenoord-forward/59036/#B3wkdmjgX1QJMRkw.99|work=Inside Futbol|accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>}}\n\nIn April 2008, at the age of sixteen, Guidetti signed a three-year deal with [[Manchester City F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester City]].<ref name=\"Scout\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imscouting.com/global-news-article/The-Swedish-Wayne-Rooney/7571/|title=Player to Watch \u2013 John Guidetti|date=6 May 2010|accessdate=8 June 2010|work=imscouting.com|publisher=IMScouting}}</ref> [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Inter Milan]], [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]], [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] and [[Ajax Cape Town F.C.|Ajax Cape Town]] ([[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]'s feeder club in South Africa), among others, had all been in competition for securing his services.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dn.se/sport/fotboll/talangen-ar-redo-att-satsa-allt-1.794056|title=Talent is ready to do everything|language=Swedish|date=6 February 2009|accessdate=8 June 2010|work=dn.se|publisher=Dagens Nyheter|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528103456/http://www.dn.se/sport/fotboll/talangen-ar-redo-att-satsa-allt-1.794056|archivedate=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Manchester City===\nManchester City's manager at the time, Sven Goran Eriksson, spotted Guidetti's talent in his native Sweden, and immediately signed him. Guidetti enjoyed a fine first season with the [[Manchester City F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester City]] under-18 team, scoring 13 times in 13 appearances. He also marked his reserve team debut with a remarkable [[hat-trick]] against a [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] side containing several seasoned campaigners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/222/transfer-zone/2010/05/27/1945376/roberto-mancini-set-to-hand-swedish-youngsterjohn-guidetti|title=Roberto Mancini set to hand Swedish youngster John Guidetti first-team chance at Manchester City \u2013 Report|date=27 May 2010|accessdate=8 June 2010|publisher=goal.com}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to IF Brommapojkarna====\nIn 2010, he went out on loan to his old club [[IF Brommapojkarna|Brommapojkarna]], impressing by scoring three goals and racking up three assists in only eight appearances.<ref name=\"Scout\" />\n\n====Return to Manchester City====\n[[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]'s manager, [[Roberto Mancini]], wanted to see how the youngster matched up alongside the City first team, so he handed him a chance to impress on the club's pre-season tour in the United States during the summer of 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/sport/football/manchester_city/s/1241230_city_set_to_launch_guidetti\n|title=City set to launch Guidetti|date=27 May 2010|accessdate=8 June 2010|work=menmedia.co.uk|publisher=Manchester Evening News}}</ref> During this American tour, Guidetti managed to make his debut for the Manchester City first team, coming on as a sub in the second half in a match against [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting Lisbon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/American-Pre-season-tour/2010/July/US-Tour-City-v-Sporting-match-report|title=US Tour: City slip to defeat|work=mcfc.co.uk|publisher=(Manchester City Football Club)|date=24 July 2010|accessdate=4 February 2011}}</ref>\nTwo months later back in England, Guidetti went on to make his full debut in a competitive match for the Manchester City first team when he was selected as striker for the starting lineup in the League Cup third round match against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on 22 September 2010, in which he provided the assist for City's only goal in the game.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/9010120.stm|title=West Brom \u2013 Manchester City|date=22 September 2010|accessdate=22 September 2010|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation }}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Burnley====\nOn 25 November 2010, Guidetti signed an initial one-month loan deal with [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], with a possible option for Burnley to extend the loan when it expired on 1 January 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/b/burnley/9228019.stm|title=Burnley sign Manchester City striker John Guidetti |date=25 November 2010|accessdate=4 February 2011|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation\n}}</ref> On 26 December 2010, in his first start for Burnley, he scored his first goal in a 2\u20131 victory at [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/9306376.stm|title=Barnsley 1 \u2013 2 Burnley|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=26 December 2010|accessdate=29 December 2010}}</ref>\nManchester City would not extend his loan spell at Burnley, John was called back to parent club on 31 December 2010 to subsequently be added to Manchester City's registered 25-man squad for the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] competition.\n\n====Twente controversy====\nGuidetti's development contract with [[Manchester City F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester City]] was due to run out in July 2011. In late May, he visited [[Netherlands|Dutch]] club [[FC Twente|Twente]] with his father and several [[Sweden|Swedish]], [[Netherlands|Dutch]] and British media outlets reported he had signed a pre agreement with the Dutch club.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fotboll.expressen.se/internationellt/1.2463022/nu-blir-guidetti-lag-kamrat-med-bajrami|title=Now Guidetti team-mate with Bajrami|language=Swedish|date=8 June 2011|accessdate=29 October 2011|work=Sportchef Expressen.se|publisher=AB Kv\u00e4llstidningen Expressen|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008001246/http://fotboll.expressen.se/internationellt/1.2463022/nu-blir-guidetti-lag-kamrat-med-bajrami|archive-date=8 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fotbollskanalen.se/1.2151882/2011/05/25/guidetti_gar_till_twente_skrivit_pa_fyraarskontrakt|title=Guidetti goes to Twente \u2013 written on four-year contract|language=Swedish|date=25 May 2011|accessdate=29 October 2011|work=Fotbollskanalen.se|publisher=TV4 AB\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fotbollskanalen.se/1.2158774/2011/05/30/bajrami_tipsade_twente_om_guidetti|title=Bajrami tipped Twente on Guidetti |language=Swedish|date=30 May 2011|accessdate=29 October 2011|work=Fotbollskanalen.se|publisher=TV4 AB\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11906_6952861,00.html|title=City striker set for Twente|date=26 May 2011|accessdate=29 October 2011|work=www.skysports.com|publisher=skySPORTS\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.setanta.com/ien/Articles/2011/05/26/City-teen-set-to-go-Dutch/gnid-95537/|title=Guidetti to leave City|date=26 May 2011|accessdate=29 October 2011|work=setanta.com|publisher=Setanta Sports|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612120033/http://www.setanta.com/ien/Articles/2011/05/26/City-teen-set-to-go-Dutch/gnid-95537/|archivedate=12 June 2011}}</ref> In mid June, reports indicated that there were problems with this agreement. Twente understood they had a [[Bosman ruling|Bosman deal]] agreed with Guidetti's camp, but agent Per Jonsson insisted nothing had been agreed upon in contract. Twente chairman Joop Munsterman said: \"We do not know if Mr. Jonsson is his agent. We have done business with Mike [Guidetti] (the father of the player). The most important thing for a young player like Guidetti is that he plays a lot of games. For that reason, Twente is the logical choice.\" <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fcupdate.nl/voetbalnieuws/178291/komst-guidetti-naar-twente-op-losse-schroeven/|title=Guidetti coming to Twente for loose screws|language=Dutch|date=14 June 2011|accessdate=29 October 2011|work=fcupdate.nl|publisher=JHED Media Ltd}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/fctwente/10017825/__Problemen_rond_transfer_Guidetti__.html|title=Problems surrounding Guidetti transfer|language=Dutch|date=14 June 2011|accessdate=29 October 2011|work=telegraaf.nl|publisher=Telegraaf Media Nederland|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301234852/http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/fctwente/10017825/__Problemen_rond_transfer_Guidetti__.html|archive-date=1 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eurosport.se/fotboll/twente-kritiserar-agenten_sto2837729/story.shtml|title=Twente criticize the agent: \"Guidetti is ready\"|language=Swedish|date=17 June 2011|accessdate=29 October 2011|work=eurosport.se|publisher=EUROSPORT}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Netherlands|Dutch]] football association ''FBO'' (Federatie Betaald Voetbal Organization), let a [[lawyer]] review the preliminary agreement between John Guidetti and Twente. The club announced that the contract should be regarded as valid. \u2013 \"In our opinion it is a valid contract. We look forward to welcoming John for his first practice 1 July\", said Twente chairman Joop Munsterman to ''[[Voetbal International]]'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/fctwente/10086135/___Guidetti_op_1_juli_bij_FC_Twente___.html|title=Guidetti at FC Twente on July 1|language=Dutch|date=24 June 2011|accessdate=29 October 2011|work=telegraaf.nl|publisher=Telegraaf Media Nederland|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110829101429/http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/fctwente/10086135/___Guidetti_op_1_juli_bij_FC_Twente___.html|archive-date=29 August 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fotbollskanalen.se/1.2186791/2011/06/24/hollandska_forbundet_kontraktet_med_guidetti_galler |title=Dutch League \u2013 \"contract with Guidetti case\"|language=Swedish|date=24 June 2011|accessdate=29 October 2011|work=Fotbollskanalen.se|publisher=TV4 AB}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July 2011, Manchester City released a set of photographs as the team set off on a North American pre-season tour. Despite his alleged transfer to Twente, Guidetti was spotted in the photos taken at the airport with his Manchester City teammates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/mcfcofficial/5917104135/in/set72157627026030355/#/photos/mcfcofficial/5917104135/in/set-72157627026030355/lightbox/|title=Summer tour: Travelling |date=9 July 2011|accessdate=29 October 2011|work=Flickr.com|publisher=(Yahoo Inc.)\n}}</ref> On 19 July 2011, Guidetti was offered and signed a first team contract binding him to the club of Manchester City for three more years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,12875_7046760,00.html|title=Guidetti commits to City|date=18 July 2011|accessdate=29 October 2011|work=skysports.com|publisher=skySPORTS}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Feyenoord====\n[[File:Jeroen-zoet-keeper-rkc-waalwijk-1324915570.jpg|thumb|right|Guidetti (right) playing for [[Feyenoord]] in 2011, challenging [[RKC Waalwijk]] goalkeeper [[Jeroen Zoet]]]]\nOn the last day of the transfer window, [[Feyenoord]] and Manchester City agreed a loan deal for the rest of the 2011\u201312 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/news/team-news/2011/august/john-guidetti-loaned-to-feyenoord|title=Guidetti loaned to Feyenoord|publisher=Manchester City FC|date=31 August 2011|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref> Guidetti made his debut in the game against [[NAC Breda]] on 11 September 2011 in which he scored a penalty.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportqa.com/Feyenoord-Rotterdams-John-Guidetti-delighted-to-score-against-NAC-Breda-Dutch-Eredivisie-news-a29713|title=Feyenoord Rotterdam's John Guidetti delighted to score against NAC Breda \u2013 Dutch Eredivisie news|publisher=SportQA|date=11 September 2011|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref> He also scored a penalty in the match against [[De Graafschap]] and 2 more from the penalty spot against [[VVV-Venlo]]. He scored his first goal from open play for Feyenoord against [[Vitesse Arnhem|Vitesse]] in the 4\u20130 away win, netting two goals in the game.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.footreview.net/home/viewvideo/933/eredivisie-netherlands/vitesse-0-4-feyenoord-highlights|title=Vitesse 0 \u2013 4 Feyenoord Highlights|publisher=Foot Review|date=20 November 2011|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref> The following week he scored another crucial goal, the equaliser in a 2\u20131 away win against [[RKC Waalwijk]]. On 18 December 2011 he scored a [[hat-trick]] in Feyenoord's 3\u20132 victory against [[FC Twente]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.caughtoffside.com/2011/12/18/man-city-striker-john-guidetti-scores-hat-trick-for-feyenoord-against-fc-twente/|title=Man City Striker John Guidetti Scores Hat-Trick for Feyenoord Against FC Twente|publisher=Cuaght Offside|date=18 December 2011|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 January 2012, he scored his second consecutive hat-trick, scoring three goals in [[De Klassieker]] against [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], which Feyenoord won 4\u20132, their first victory in 6 years over the arch-rivals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/29012012/2/guidetti-hat-trick-feyenoord-sinks-ajax.html|title=Guidetti hat-trick for Feyenoord sinks Ajax|publisher=Yahoo! Eurosport/Reuters|date=29 January 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref> This helped earning him a hero status in Rotterdam, with coach Ronald Koeman describing him as \"phenomenal\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.voetbalprimeur.nl/nieuws/item/koeman-ziet-angst-guidetti-een-fenomeen|title=Koeman ziet angst: \"Guidetti een fenomeen\"|publisher=Voetbalprimeur|language=Dutch|date=30 January 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116101427/http://www.voetbalprimeur.nl/nieuws/item/koeman-ziet-angst-guidetti-een-fenomeen|archivedate=16 January 2014}}</ref> On 12 February he scored his third hat-trick since joining the club in a home game in a 3\u20131 win against Vitesse, putting him third in Europe for goals scored/minutes played, at 17 goals after 15 league appearances.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thepremierleagueowl.com/man-citys-john-guidetti-hitting-another-hat-trick-in-holland/|title=Man City's John Guidetti hitting another hat-trick in Holland|publisher=The Premier League Owl|date=12 February 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116124843/http://thepremierleagueowl.com/man-citys-john-guidetti-hitting-another-hat-trick-in-holland/|archive-date=16 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> This happened to be the third consecutive hat-trick in an [[Eredivisie]] home game, becoming the second player in the history of the league to achieve this after [[Cees Groot]] did this in 1963.<ref name=\"groot\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/feyenoord/11501089/__Guidetti_evenaart_Groot__.html|title=Guidetti evenaart Groot|publisher=De Telegraaf|language=Dutch|date=12 February 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318123259/http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/feyenoord/11501089/__Guidetti_evenaart_Groot__.html|archive-date=18 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Ove Kindvall]] was the last Swede to achieve this in the Dutch league in the 1970s, also playing for Feyenoord.<ref name=\"groot\"/> Also, Guidetti was the first Feyenoord player to score three hat-tricks in one season since [[Dirk Kuyt]] in 2004\u201305.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ad.nl/ad/nl/5610/Eredivisie/article/detail/3174628/2012/02/12/LIVE-Guidetti-scoort-meteen-na-opvallende-balwissel.dhtml|title=Guidetti zet Kuip met hattrick weer in vuur en vlam|language=Dutch|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|date=12 February 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nGuidetti scored his 18th goal from the penalty spot in his 16th league game against [[RKC Waalwijk]], and celebrated by pulling his shirt off which gave him his second yellow card in the game.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2103224/Manchester-City-John-Guidetti-costly-goal-celebration.html|title=Guid to bad! City hot shot feels wrath of boss after costly goal celebration|publisher=Daily Mail|date=18 February 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref> The opponents then equalized three minutes before the end, and Guidetti later apologized to the team, the supporters and the coach, saying it was \"one of the worst moments in my life\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11916/7535629/Guidetti-says-sorry-for-red-card|title=Guidetti says sorry for red card|publisher=Sky Sports|date=21 February 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref> Due to this red card, Guidetti missed the important game in the title challenge against [[PSV Eindhoven]] the following week. A couple of weeks later, Guidetti scored his next goal away to [[De Graafschap]] in a 3\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/news/team-news/2012/march/loan-watch-27-march-john-guidetti-back-in-form|title=Loan watch:Guidetti back in the groove|publisher=Manchester City FC|date=27 March 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref> He scored his 20th, and final, goal of the season in a 3\u20130 city-derby home win over [[Excelsior Rotterdam]] in April. Guidetti then missed the rest of the Eredivisie season, as well as [[UEFA Euro 2012]], after losing all feeling in his right leg while suffering from a mystery virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/manchester-city-john-guidetti-struck-810742|title=Mystery virus: City striker loses all feeling in his leg|publisher=The Mirror|date=28 April 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nWithout the injured Guidetti, Feyenoord managed to secure only second spot of the league, but it guaranteed them a place in the qualification rounds for the [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2012/05/06/feyenoord-claims-champions-league-spot-in-eredivisie/|title=Feyenoord claims Champions League spot in Eredivisie|publisher=Fox News|date=6 May 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref> Guidetti, who watched from home the game against [[SC Heerenveen]] which clinched second place, was then carried on the shoulders of some Feyenoord fans towards [[De Kuip]] stadium to celebrate this achievement.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://feyenoord.netwerk.to/nieuws/artikel/26521_%5BFoto%5D%20Guidetti%20op%20de%20schouders.php|title=Guidetti op de schouders|publisher=Feyenoord Network|language=Dutch|date=6 May 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref> Later on he was seen singing \"Feyenoord till I die\" with the fans at the stadium and singing a Champions League song at the pitch amongst the other players.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fr12.nl/dump/8130-guidetti--i--m-feyenoord-till-i-die-.html|title=Guidetti, I'm Feyenoord till I die.|publisher=FR 12|date=10 May 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fr12.nl/dump/8074-guidetti-zet-de-kuip-op-zijn-kop.html|title=Guidetti zet de Kuip op zijn kop|publisher=FR 12|language=Dutch|date=6 May 2012|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref> In total, Guidetti scored 20 goals and provided eight assists in 23 games for Feyenoord during this loan spell.\n\n====Struggling for fitness====\nGuidetti was back at Man City for the start of 2012\u201313, but spent the most of the season struggling to recover from the virus that curtailed his spell at Feyenoord. The severity of the disorder saw Guidetti diagnosed with an infected nerve, which caused him to lose feeling in his right leg.<ref name=\"ill\">{{cite web|last1=Beresford|first1=Jack|title=Whatever happened to Manchester City's John Guidetti?|url=http://www.ftbpro.com/posts/99607-whatever-happened-to-manchester-city-s-john-guidetti|publisher=FTB Pro|accessdate=4 November 2014|date=5 January 2013}}</ref>  Commenting about Guidetti's condition, assistant manager [[David Platt (footballer)|David Platt]] explained, \"For about two or three months he [Guidetti] couldn't do anything and it takes a long time to get that back.\"<ref name=\"ill\" />  Despite this, Guidetti signed a new three-year deal with Manchester City on 18 October 2012, keeping him at the Etihad Stadium until 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19991206 |title=Manchester City Striker John Guidetti signs new contract |date=18 October 2012 |accessdate=18 October 2012 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballfriendsonline.com/blogs/2012/10/18/outrageous-guidetti-shows-why-man-city-have-given-him-new-3.html|title=Outrageous Guidetti shows why Man City have given him new 4 year contract|date=18 October 2012|accessdate=18 October 2012|publisher=Footballfriends.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022113017/http://www.footballfriendsonline.com/blogs/2012/10/18/outrageous-guidetti-shows-why-man-city-have-given-him-new-3.html|archivedate=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe finally returned to playing football on 14 January 2013 when he played in the first half of an [[2012\u201313 Professional U21 Development League|Under 21 League]] match between City and [[Reading F.C. Under-21s and Academy|Reading U21s]], scoring the opening goal in a 3\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brennan|first1=Stuart|title=John Guidetti joy at Blues return|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/john-guidetti-joy-at-blues-return-1210318|publisher=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=4 November 2014|date=15 January 2013}}</ref>  Guidetti scored a further five goals in his next six games for the Development Side,<ref name=\"knee\">{{cite web|last1=Dawson|first1=Rob|title=Fresh-faced Blues get a fresh start|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/fresh-faced-blues-fresh-start-3869404|publisher=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=4 November 2014|date=18 May 2013}}</ref> before sucummbing to a knee injury which later required surgery.<ref name=\"knee\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dawson|first1=Rob|title=Pellegrini praise for Guidetti recovery|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manuel-pellegrini-praise-john-guidetti-6207834|publisher=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=4 November 2014|date=18 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Stoke City====\nOn 14 January 2014, Guidetti joined [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on loan for the remainder of the [[2013\u201314 Stoke City F.C. season|2013\u201314]] season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Guidetti Joins On Loan|url=http://www.stokecityfc.com/news/article/guidetti-joins-on-loan-1294155.aspx|work=Stoke City F.C|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Transfer window: Stephen Ireland & John Guidetti join Stoke City|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25720354|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> He made his debut on 18 January 2014 coming on as a substitute in a 1\u20130 defeat against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Crystal Palace 1\u20130 Stoke|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25693671|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> After not playing in Stoke's next match against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the [[FA Cup]], Guidetti vented his frustration towards manager [[Mark Hughes]] to the Swedish media.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Guidetti annoyed to spend another week on the bench after Chelsea defeat|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-John-Guidetti-annoyed-spend-week-bench/story-20503993-detail/story.html|work=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=30 March 2014}}</ref> Guidetti later insisted that he was not being disrespectful to Hughes.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Guidetti denies disrespecting Mark Hughes|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-John-Guidetti-denies-disrespecting/story-20806645-detail/story.html|work=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=30 March 2014}}</ref> He had an unsuccessful time at Stoke as he made just six appearances, all of them as a substitute.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|56208|2013|name=John Guidetti|access-date=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Celtic====\nOn 4 September 2014, Guidetti joined [[Scottish Premiership]] side [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] on loan for the [[2014\u201315 Celtic F.C. season|2014\u201315]] season,<ref>{{cite web|title=John Guidetti joins Celtic|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/6578|website=Celtic|accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref> but was ineligible for the [[UEFA Europe League]] group stages.<ref>[https://archive.today/20140905142927/http://m.stv.tv/sport/football/clubs/celtic/290993-celtics-europa-league-squad-confirmed-john-guidetti-not-included/ Celtic's Europa League squad confirmed] STV. 5 September 2014. Retrieved 22 February 2015.</ref> He made his debut nine days later, replacing [[Scott Brown (footballer, born June 1985)|Scott Brown]] for the final 29 minutes of a 2\u20131 home win over [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Southwick|first1=Andrew|title=Celtic 2\u20131 Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29090522|accessdate=13 September 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=13 September 2014}}</ref> On 24 September he scored his first Celtic goal, opening a 3\u20130 home win over [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] in the last 16 of the [[Scottish League Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Moffat|first=Colin|title=Celtic 3\u20130 Hearts|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29233038|accessdate=25 September 2014|work=BBC Sport|date=24 September 2014}}</ref> Three days later he scored his first Premiership goals, netting both as Celtic won 2\u20131 at [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Campbell|first1=Andy|title=St Mirren 1\u20132 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29289908|accessdate=27 September 2014|work=BBC Sport|date=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe scored a hat-trick on 29 October, as Celtic advanced to the semi-finals of the [[Scottish League Cup]] with a 6\u20130 win over [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mcleod|first1=Liam|title=Celtic 6\u20130 Partick Thistle|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29718349|accessdate=30 October 2014|work=BBC Sport|date=29 October 2014}}</ref> His treble was the 15th hat-trick scored at Celtic by a Swedish player.<ref>[https://twitter.com/splstats/status/527565231493742592 SPL Stats on Twitter] Twitter. 29 October 2014. Retrieved 9 May 2015.</ref> Three days later he scored the only goal in a league win over [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]], his ninth goal in his last seven games.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Richard|title=Celtic 1\u20130 Inverness|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29767941|accessdate=1 November 2014|work=BBC Sport|date=1 November 2014}}</ref> He was named as the Premiership Player of the Month for October 2014, with six goals in four games, all won by Celtic.<ref name=\"pom1014\">{{cite news|title=Celtic: striker John Guidetti lands October SPFL player award|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29932441|accessdate=17 November 2014|work=BBC Sport|date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nGuidetti scored a penalty in Celtic's 4\u20130 win at [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] in the fourth round of the [[Scottish Cup]] on 30 November; its awarding was controversial as the Hearts players protested that he had dived under pressure from [[Brad McKay]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Southwick|first1=Andrew|title=Hearts 0\u20134 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30166217|accessdate=30 November 2014|work=BBC Sport|date=30 November 2014}}</ref> It was his 11th goal in just 10 games for Celtic,<ref name=11in10>[http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12040/9711791/spfl-celtic-manager-ronny-deila-backing-john-guidetti-to-start-scoring-again SPFL: Celtic manager Ronny Deila backing John Guidetti to start scoring again] Sky Sports. 14 February 2015. Retrieved 22 February 2015.</ref> after which Guidetti embarked on run of  10 games without a goal,<ref>[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/inter-milan-boss-roberto-mancini-5166387 Inter Milan boss Roberto Mancini fears] Daily Record. 15 February 2015. Retrieved 22 January 2015.</ref> and lost his place in the starting eleven to [[Leigh Griffiths]].<ref name=11in10/> However, on as a second-half substitute in the [[UEFA Europa League]] match against [[Internazionale|Inter Milan]] on 19 February, he rescued a 3\u20133 draw for Celtic with a stoppage-time equaliser,<ref name=3v3InterMilan>[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-match-reports/celtic-3-inter-milan-3-5195871 Celtic 3: Inter 3] Daily Record. 20 February 2015. Retrieved 22 February 2015.</ref> controlling a lobbed pass onto his chest before volleying into the roof of the net.<ref name=3v3InterMilan/>\n\nOn 15 March, Guidetti won his first silverware at Celtic, as they defeated [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] 2\u20130 in the [[2015 Scottish League Cup Final|League Cup Final]] at [[Hampden Park]]. He came on in the 69th minute for Griffiths, and 15 minutes later when [[James Forrest (footballer)|James Forrest]] won a penalty, Celtic players wanted Guidetti to take it; Forrest took it himself and it was saved by [[Rados\u0142aw Cierzniak]].<ref name=bbcfinal>{{cite news|title=Dundee Utd 0\u20132 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31785677|accessdate=15 March 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=14 March 2015|first=Richard|last=Wilson}}</ref> Prior to that, Guidetti had assisted Forest for Celtic's second goal.<ref>[http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/celtic-2-0-dundee-united-hoops-win-league-cup-1-3719080 Celtic 2\u20130 Dundee United] The Scotsman. 16 March 2015. Retrieved 23 February 2015.</ref> On 19 April, in a Scottish Cup semi-final at Hampden Park, he came on for Griffiths in extra time and equalised against Inverness, although Celtic eventually lost 2\u20133.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lindsay|first1=Clive|title=Inverness CT 3\u20132 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32089585|accessdate=19 April 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=19 April 2015}}</ref> It was his 15th goal of the season.<ref>[http://hereisthecity.com/en-gb/2015/05/02/report-celtic-loanee-john-guidetti-is-ignoring-calls-from-feyeno/ Report: Celtic loanee John Guidetti is ignoring calls from Feyenoord over his signature] HITC. May 2015. Retrieved 9 May 2015.</ref> Guidetti finished the season with 15 goals from 35 appearances for Celtic.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=56208&season_id=144 John Guidetti career stats 2014\u201315] Soccer Base. Retrieved 29 May 2015.</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 2014\u201315 season, it was announced that parent club Manchester City did not intend to offer Guidetti a new contract, and would become a free agent once his contract expired along with teammate [[Micah Richards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/transfer-centre/article/168/9880981/john-guidetti-released |title=Lampard among released players |date=10 June 2015 |publisher=SportingLife |accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Celta===\nOn 11 July 2015, Guidetti signed for [[La Liga]] club [[Celta de Vigo]] on a [[free transfer (association football)|free transfer]], after agreeing to a five-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33493812 |title=John Guidetti: Celta Vigo sign ex-Manchester City striker |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 July 2015 |accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> He made his debut on 23 August as a 69th-minute substitute for [[Hugo Mallo]] in a 2\u20131 win at [[Levante UD|Levante]], and scored his first goal on 23 September, a volley to confirm a 4\u20131 win over reigning champions [[FC Barcelona]] five minutes after entering as a replacement for [[Iago Aspas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Iago Aspas scores twice as Celta Vigo give Barcelona shock thrashing|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/sep/23/celta-vigo-barcelona-match-report|accessdate=24 September 2015|agency=Reuters|publisher=The Guardian|date=23 September 2015}}</ref> On 27 January 2016, Guidetti scored with a 25-metre volley in a 3\u20132 win over [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] in the quarter-finals of the [[Copa del Rey]], helping his side reach the semi-finals of the Cup for the first time in 15 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celta Vigo shock Atl\u00e9tico Madrid to progress to Copa del Rey last four|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jan/27/atletico-madrid-celta-vigo-copa-del-rey-quarter-final|accessdate=1 April 2016|work=The Guardian|date=27 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Alav\u00e9s===\nOn 8 January 2018, Guidetti was loaned to fellow first division club [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s]], until the end of [[2017\u201318 La Liga|the season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deportivoalaves.com/noticia/el-deportivo-alaves-incorpora-a-john-guidetti|title=El Deportivo Alav\u00e9s incorpora a John Guidetti|trans-title=Deportivo Alav\u00e9s sign John Guidetti|publisher=Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|language=es|date=8 January 2018|access-date=29 May 2018}}</ref> On 29 May, he signed a permanent four-year deal with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://as.com/futbol/2018/05/29/primera/1527587645_008095.html|title=Guidetti, del Alav\u00e9s hasta 2022|trans-title=Guidetti, of Alav\u00e9s until 2022|publisher=[[Diario AS]]|language=es|date=29 May 2018|access-date=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 January 2020, Guidetti was loaned out to [[Hannover 96]] for the rest of the 2019\u201320 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hannover96.de/aktuelles/news/details/26717-schwedischer-nationalstuermer-fuer-96-john-guidetti-kommt-aus-alaves.html|title=Schwedischer Nationalst\u00fcrmer f\u00fcr 96: Guidetti kommt aus Alav\u00e9s|publisher=Hannover 96|lang=German|date=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Oscar Hiljemark and John Guidetti in June 2015.jpg|thumb|right|Guidetti celebrating the [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2015 European Under-21 Championship]]]]\n\n===Youth===\nGuidetti played 14 matches and scored 14 goals for Sweden's Under-19 national squads, including four goals against the Netherlands. Although initially considered to be beyond selection to play for the [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden U21]] team (who were leading their European Championship qualifying group at the time) in the June 2010 fixtures against [[Israel national under-21 football team|Israel]] and [[Montenegro national under-21 football team|Montenegro]], Guidetti ultimately got his chance to play at this higher level as a replacement for the injured first choice striker [[Agon Mehmeti]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/sportbladet/fotboll/landslagsfotboll/u21/article7211753.ab|title=Hallenius and Guidetti called in to the European Championship qualifiers|language=Swedish|date=29 May 2010|accessdate=8 June 2010|work=aftonbladet.se|publisher=SPORT Bladet}}</ref>\nGuidetti accordingly took his place in the Sweden U21 team's starting eleven that manage to win away 1\u20130 against [[Israel national under-21 football team|Israel]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dn.se/sport/fotboll/sveriges-u21-herrar-slog-israel-1.1116961|title=Sweden's under-21 men beat Israel|language=Swedish|date=4 June 2010|accessdate=8 June 2010|work=dn.se|publisher=Dagens Nyheter|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100607033121/http://www.dn.se/sport/fotboll/sveriges-u21-herrar-slog-israel-1.1116961|archivedate=7 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nGuidetti earnt his next international cap when he was included in the [[Sweden national youth football team|Sweden U19]] team rather than the Sweden U21 team because according to Swedish Under-21 national team coach, [[J\u00f6rgen Lennartsson]], they had even \"greater need\" for him back in the younger team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fotbollskanalen.se/1.1733847/2010/08/03/har_ar_lennartssons_trupp_till_u21_landslaget_ingen_guidetti_med|title=Here is Lenny's squad for the Under-21 squad \u2013 no Guidetti|language=Swedish|date=3 August 2010|accessdate=10 September 2010|work=Fotbollskanalen.se|publisher=TV4 AB\n}}</ref> He scored after just four minutes in his first game back with the Under-19 line-up against [[Poland national under-19 football team|Poland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.expressen.se/sport/sanktan/stockholm/1.2092732/p92-saker-3-1-seger-mot-polen |title=P92: Secure 3\u20131 win against Poland |language=Swedish|date=11 August 2010|accessdate=11 August 2010|work=Expressen.se|publisher=AB Kv\u00e4llstidningen Expressen}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sport.onet.pl/pilka-nozna/reprezentacja/mlodzi-polacy-nie-sprostali-szwedom,1,3416526,wiadomosc.html|title=Young Poles are no match for the Swedes|language=Polish|date=10 August 2010|accessdate=10 August 2010|work=Sport.onet.pl|publisher=Grupa Onet.pl SA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617111648/http://sport.onet.pl/pilka-nozna/reprezentacja/mlodzi-polacy-nie-sprostali-szwedom,1,3416526,wiadomosc.html|archivedate=17 June 2011}}</ref> After the Sweden U21 team suffered a surprise home defeat against Israel without Guidetti, John was recalled once again to play for this team in its decisive qualifying match against [[Bulgaria national under-19 football team|Bulgaria]], where he created the winning and only goal for Sweden in a 1\u20130 victory.\n\nAt the [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2015 European Under-21 Championship]] in the Czech Republic, Guidetti equalised as Sweden came from behind to defeat [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy]] 2\u20131 in their opening group game in [[Olomouc]].<ref>{{cite news|title=U21 round-up: Sweden stun Italy|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/9889364/u21-round-up-sweden-stun-italy|accessdate=21 June 2015|publisher=Sky Sports|date=18 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33063307|title=England U21 0\u20131 Portugal U21|publisher=BBC Sport|last1=Jurejko|first1=Jonathan|date=18 June 2015|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref> He took and scored Sweden's first spot-kick in the [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] in [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship Final|the final]] against [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal]], which his team won after a 0\u20130 draw in [[Prague]].<ref name=\"uefa21\">{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2015/matches/round=2000411/match=2015383/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Sweden beat Portugal on penalties to win U21 title|publisher=UEFA.com|date=30 June 2015|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Senior===\nGuidetti debuted with the [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] senior squad on 29 February 2012 in a friendly away to [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]], coming on as a half-time substitute.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dn.se/sport/fotboll/godkant-debut-av-guidetti|title=Zlatan wants Guidetti in Euro 2012|language=Swedish|date=29 February 2012|accessdate=29 February 2012|work=dn.se|publisher=Dagens Nyheter|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229234641/http://www.dn.se/sport/fotboll/godkant-debut-av-guidetti|archivedate=29 February 2012}}</ref> He had to wait over two-and-a-half years for his second cap, replacing [[Isaac Thelin]] for the last 23 minutes of a 1\u20130 friendly defeat to [[France national football team|France]] in [[Marseille]] on 18 November 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=France 1\u20130 Sweden: Varane secures win for dominant Bleus|url=http://www.goal.com/en/match/france-vs-sweden/1946143/report|accessdate=19 November 2014|work=Goal.com|date=18 November 2014}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Sweden on 5 June 2016, netting the third in a 3\u20130 friendly win over [[Wales national football team|Wales]].<ref name=1st>{{cite news|last=Davies|first=Jack (5 June 2016)|url=http://www.goal.com/en-za/match/sweden-vs-wales/2206332/report|title=Sweden 3\u20130 Wales: Coleman's men winless in four ahead of Euros|accessdate=5 June 2016|website=Goal}}</ref>\n\nHe was a squad player for Sweden at [[Euro 2016]].<ref name=\"goal.com\"/>\n\nIn May 2018 he was named in [[Sweden national football team|Sweden's]] [[Sweden national football team|23 man squad]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>http://www.goal.com/en-gb/amp/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGuidetti's paternal grandfather is [[Italy|Italian]] and his paternal grandmother is half [[Swedes|Swedish]], half [[Brazil]]ian.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.svtplay.se/video/323068/del-4-av-12 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=3 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002202648/http://www.svtplay.se/video/323068/del-4-av-12 |archivedate= 2 October 2012 }}</ref> Guidetti has lived in [[Kenya]] on two occasions with his father Mike, mother Susanne and his sister Carmen. Guidetti credits playing football with older children from the poorer slum areas of [[Kibera]] and [[Mathare]] as an important step in his development on and off the field, and founded a NGO that helps children in the area.<ref>http://www.guidettifoundation.org/</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2015, Swedish music group Badpojken made a song about Guidetti, called \"Johnny G (The Guidetti Song)\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Ystadsgrupp har gjort hyllingsl\u00e5t till John Guidetti|url=http://www.ystadsallehanda.se/sport/ystadsgrupp-har-gjort-hyllingslat-till-john-guidetti/|accessdate=13 November 2017|work=Ystads Allehanda|date=7 July 2015}}</ref> It peaked [[List of number-one singles and albums in Sweden|number 1]] at the [[Sverigetopplistan|Swedish music charts]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Badpojken \u2013 Johnny G (The Guidetti Song)|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/1642f1/Badpojken-Johnny-G-(The-Guidetti-Song)|accessdate=13 November 2017|work=Ultratop}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played on 18 May 2019}}<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=136381&league=ENG.1&season=2009&cc=5739|title= Statistics|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|accessdate=22 September 2009 }}</ref><ref>[https://svenskfotboll.se/allsvenskan/person/?playerid=5856 John Guidetti \u2014 svenskfotboll.se]</ref><ref name=\"sway\">{{cite web|title= J. GUIDETTI|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/john-guidetti/126941/|publisher=Soccerway.com|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[IF Brommapojkarna]]\n|[[2008 Superettan|2008]]\n|[[Superettan]]\n|2||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0\n|-\n|[[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Manchester City F.C. season|2010\u201311]]\n|[[Premier League]]\n|0||0||0||0||1||0||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[IF Brommapojkarna]] (loan)\n|[[2010 Allsvenskan|2010]]\n|[[Allsvenskan]]\n|8||3||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||8||3\n|-\n|[[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] (loan)\n|[[2010\u201311 Burnley F.C. season|2010\u201311]]\n|[[Football League Championship|Championship]]\n|4||1||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||1\n|-\n|[[Feyenoord]] (loan)\n|[[2011\u201312 Eredivisie|2011\u201312]]\n|[[Eredivisie]]\n|23||20||0||0||0||0||0||0||23||20\n|-\n|[[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] (loan)\n|[[2013\u201314 Stoke City F.C. season|2013\u201314]]\n|Premier League\n|6||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||0\n|-\n|[[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] (loan)\n|[[2014\u201315 Celtic F.C. season|2014\u201315]]\n|[[Scottish Premiership]]\n|24||8||5||2||4||4||2||1||35||15\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Celta Vigo]]\n|[[2015\u201316 La Liga|2015\u201316]]\n|rowspan=3|[[La Liga]]\n|35||7||8||5||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||43||12\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 La Liga|2016\u201317]]\n|23||4||6||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||13||4||42||9\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Celta de Vigo season|2017\u201318]]\n|8||0||2||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||10||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!66!!11!!16!!7!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||13!!4!!95!!22\n|-\n|[[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]] (loan)\n|[[2017\u201318 Deportivo Alav\u00e9s season|2017\u201318]]\n|rowspan=2|[[La Liga]]\n|17||3||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||19||3\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]]\n|[[2018\u201319 Deportivo Alav\u00e9s season|2018\u201319]]\n|22||2||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||24||2\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!39!!5!!4!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0!!0!!43!!5\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!172!!48!!25!!9!!5!!4!!15!!5!!217!!66\n|}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|match played 18 November 2019}}<ref name=\"NFT\">{{NFT player|id=46637|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ International statistics\n|-\n!National team\n!Year\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]\n|2012||1||0\n|-\n|2014||1||0\n|-\n|2015||3||0\n|-\n|2016||12||1\n|-\n|2017||2||0\n|-\n|2018||7||1\n|-\n|2019||2||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total!!28!!3\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list Sweden's goal tally first.''<ref name=\"NFT\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ International goals by date, venue, cap, opponent, score, result and competition\n|-\n!scope=col|No.\n!scope=col data-sort-type=date|Date\n!scope=col|Venue\n!scope=col|Cap\n!scope=col|Opponent\n!scope=col|Score\n!scope=col|Result\n!scope=col|Competition\n|-\n!scope=row|1.\n|5 June 2016||rowspan=3|[[Friends Arena]], [[Solna Municipality|Solna]], Sweden||align=center|9||{{fb|WAL}}||align=center|3\u20130||align=center|3\u20130||rowspan=2|[[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]\n|-\n!scope=row|2.\n|16 October 2018||align=center|25||{{fb|SVK}}||align=center|1\u20130||align=center|1\u20131\n|-\n!scope=row|3.\n|18 November 2019||align=center|28||{{fb|FRO}}||align=center|3\u20130||align=center|3\u20130|||[[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying Group F|UEFA Euro 2020 qualification]]\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Celtic'''\n*[[Scottish Premiership]]: [[2014\u201315 Scottish Premiership|2014\u201315]]<ref name=\"sway\" />\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[2014\u201315 Scottish League Cup|2015]]<ref name=bbcfinal />\n\n'''Sweden U21'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]: [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2015]]<ref name=\"uefa21\" />\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[List of Scottish Professional Football League monthly award winners|Scottish Premiership Player of the Month]]: [[List of Scottish Professional Football League monthly award winners#2014.E2.80.9315 season|October 2014]]<ref name=\"pom1014\" />\n*UEFA European Under-21 Championship Bronze Boot: [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship#Golden Boot|2015]]<ref name=\"golden boot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/news/newsid=2262324.html|title=Czech striker Kliment wins Golden Boot award|publisher=UEFA.com|date=30 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{BDFutbol}}\n*{{Soccerway}}\n*{{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130213183732/http://www.eliteprospects.com/football/player.php?player=989 |date=13 February 2013 |title=Elitefootball Profile }}\n* {{Svenskfotboll|fid=492667|pid=5856|archive=20160305202634}}\n\n{{Hannover 96 squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Sweden squads\n| bg = #FFF01C\n| fg = #005B99\n| bordercolor = #005B99\n| list1 = \n{{Sweden squad UEFA Euro 2016}}\n{{Sweden squad 2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Copa del Rey top scorers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guidetti, John}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Brazilian descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Swedish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Mathare United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ligi Ndogo S.C. players]]\n[[Category:IF Brommapojkarna players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Feyenoord players]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:RC Celta de Vigo players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Alav\u00e9s players]]\n[[Category:Hannover 96 players]]\n[[Category:Superettan players]]\n[[Category:Allsvenskan players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:2. Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Sweden youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2016 players]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "2a04:4a43:507f:c7a6:5d8a:dc4c:2ac1:bfd6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Guidetti"}
{"title_page": "Walther P99", "text_new": "{{about|the semi-automatic pistol||P99 (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name=Walther P99\n| image= Walther P99 9x19mm.png\n| image_size = 300\n|caption=A first-generation 9mm version, with a green polymer frame.\n|origin=Germany\n|type=[[Semi-automatic pistol]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged=yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n|service=1997-present\n|used_by=See ''[[Walther P99#Users|Users]]''\n<!-- Production history -->\n|designer=Horst Wesp\n|design_date=1994\u20131996\n|manufacturer=[[Walther arms|Carl Walther GmbH Sportwaffen]]\n|production_date=1997\u2013present\n|number=\n|variants=P99QPQ, P99 Military, P990 (P99DAO), P99QA, P99QNL, P99AS, P99TA, P99C, P99C AS, P99C QA, P99C DAO, P99 RAD, P99Q and [[Smith & Wesson SW99|SW99]]\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight={{convert|630|g|oz|abbr=on}} (9\u00d719mm)<br/>{{convert|655|g|abbr=on}} (.40 S&W)\n|length={{convert|180|mm|in|abbr=on}} (9\u00d719mm)<br/> {{convert|184|mm|abbr=on|1}} (.40 S&W)\n|part_length={{convert|102|mm|abbr=on|1}} (9\u00d719mm)<br/> {{convert|106|mm|abbr=on|1}} (.40 S&W)\n|width={{convert|29|mm|abbr=on|1}} (9\u00d719mm)<br/>{{convert|32|mm|abbr=on|1}} (.40 S&W)\n|height={{convert|135|mm|abbr=on|1}}\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n|cartridge=[[9\u00d719mm Parabellum]]<br/> [[.40 S&W]]<br/> [[9\u00d721mm IMI]]\n|action=[[Recoil operation|Short recoil operated]], locked breech\n|range={{convert|50|m|yd|abbr=on}} (9\u00d719mm)\n|velocity={{convert|408|m/s|0|abbr=on}} (9\u00d719mm) <br/> {{convert|344|m/s|abbr=on|0}} (.40 S&W)\n|feed=9\u00d719mm: 10-, 15-, 17- or 20-round detachable [[box magazine]]<br/> .40 S&W: 10-, 12-, or 14-round box magazine\n|sights=Interchangeable 3-dot notch sight\n}}\n\nThe '''Walther P99''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8valt\u0250|lang}}) is a [[semi-automatic pistol]] developed by the German company [[Walther arms|Carl Walther GmbH Sportwaffen]] of [[Ulm]] for law enforcement, security forces and the civilian shooting market as a replacement for the [[Walther P5]] and the [[Walther P88|P88]]. The P99 and its variants are also made under licence by [[\u0141ucznik Arms Factory|Fabryka Broni Radom]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.fabrykabroni.pl/?d=114|title=P99 Personal Semiautomatic Pistol|accessdate=2010-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204045656/http://en.fabrykabroni.pl/?d=114|archive-date=2010-02-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDesign work on this new generation sidearm began in 1994, and the handgun was presented in 1997 with series production commencing that same year.<ref name=\"Walther P99 at World Guns\">{{cite web|url=http://world.guns.ru/handguns/hg14-e.htm|title=Walther P99 at World Guns|accessdate=24 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914213257/http://world.guns.ru/handguns/hg14-e.htm|archive-date=2010-09-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> The weapon was first introduced chambered in [[9\u00d719mm Parabellum]].\n\nThe pistol is used by the [[Landespolizei|German Police]] in [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] and [[Rhineland-Palatinate]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dienstwaffen.di.funpic.de/herstellerwxyz/walther/5119799b3208d9102.html|title=P 99 Q|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426010701/http://dienstwaffen.di.funpic.de/herstellerwxyz/walther/5119799b3208d9102.html|archive-date=2012-04-26|url-status=|access-date=2018-09-15}}</ref> and has been ordered by [[Bremen]], [[Hamburg]] and [[Schleswig-Holstein]], the [[Law enforcement in Poland|Polish Police]] and the [[Finnish Army]]'s special forces and military police, where it carries the designation '''PIST 2003''' (''Pistooli 2003'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mil.fi/maavoimat/kalustoesittely/index.dsp?level=65&equipment=170|title=Finnish Army equipment page PIST 2003|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> The Walther P99Q was also chosen in 2012 to replace older pistols and revolvers of the Finnish Police, Customs and Border Guard. This gun has also been chosen to replace the [[Walther P5]] of the Dutch Police in 2013.<ref name=\"hbl.fi\">{{cite web|url=http://hbl.fi/nyheter/2012-01-18/polisens-nya-tjanstevapen-kommer-fran-tyskland|title=hbl.fi|work=Hbl.fi - Finlands ledande nyhetssajt p\u00e5 svenska|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> In 2014 the Walther P99Q was also chosen to replace the [[Makarov PM]] of the [[Estonian Police]] and Border Guard Board.\n\n==Product evolution==\nThe Walther P99 was modified several times throughout its production history, as were the [[Magazine (firearms)|magazines]]. When the P99 was introduced the magazine capacities were 16 rounds for 9\u00d719mm Parabellum and 12 rounds for .40 S&W. Magazines had witness holes on both sides. Later the magazine capacities were reduced to 15 rounds for 9\u00d719mm Parabellum and 11 rounds for .40 S&W while witness holes were introduced at the rear of the magazine to view the loading condition.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130417210026/http://www.lundestudio.com/WaltherP99FAQ/III/6.html Are pre-ban full-capacity magazines available for the P99? at lundestudio.com WaltherP99 FAQ via Wayback Machine]</ref>\n\n===Second generation models===\nWalther presented a redesigned second generation P99 in 2004, incorporating a modified trigger guard that eliminated the \"ski hump\", which is clearly visible in the accompanying first generation images. This was done to address user comfort concerns regarding the previous style.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.all4shooters.com/en/Shooting/pistols/Walther-P99-20-years-tested-models/|title=20 Years of the Walther P99. The top models tested - Walther - Pistols - Article - all4shooters.com|last=GmbH|first=Hamza Malalla and Matthias S. Recktenwald. Photos: Michael Schippers, Heinz D. Kupsch, Carl Walther|website=all4shooters.com (EN)|language=en|access-date=2018-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://improb.com/walther-p99/|title=Walther P99 {{!}} Improb|date=2017-10-09|work=Improb|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref> The first generation P99 pistols had a slide release at the left side of the frame while second generation guns may have optional ambidextrous slide stop release levers. Walther also took the opportunity to redesign the slide so the user could grip it more easily, and notably, change the proprietary accessory rail to a [[Weaver rail mount|Weaver]] type.\nSome models built in 2005 and all later models received one more design change, an elongated magazine release.<ref name=\"Walther P99 at World Guns\"/>\n\n==Design details==\n[[File:WP99 3.jpg|thumb|left|Walther P99 with the slide locked back displaying its vertical barrel tilt.]]\n\nThe Walther P99 is a [[Recoil operation#Short recoil operation|short recoil]]-operated locked breech [[semi-automatic pistol]] that uses a modified [[John Browning|Browning]] cam-lock system adapted from the [[Browning Hi-Power|Hi-Power]] pistol. The P99 has a glassfiber-reinforced polymer frame and steel slide assembly. It can be broken down into its main parts or field stripped with a take down catch without the help of tools.\n\nIt uses an internal [[Trigger (firearms)#Pre-set .28striker or hammer.29|striker]] as opposed to an external [[hammer (firearms)|hammer]], with a red-painted striker tip that protrudes from rear of the [[pistol slide|slide]] when the gun is cocked, as well as a [[loaded chamber indicator]] on the right side of the slide.\n\nThe original, first-generation P99 had a traditional [[Trigger (firearms)#Double-action.2Fsingle-action|Double-Action/Single-Action trigger]] with a [[De-cocker#Decocker|decocker]]. When the slide is racked completely to the rear upon loading, the trigger remains in the forward position for the first shot and the Anti-Stress mode is activated, where the striker is cocked but the trigger has the length of pull of the double-action mode. The trigger travel is 14&nbsp;mm (0.55&nbsp;in) long in the Anti-Stress mode, but the most of the length is slack and is similar in feel to a two-stage rifle trigger. At the end of the anti-stress travel, the pressure noticeably increases to 4.5 pounds and the user experiences a crisp trigger break and an extremely short trigger reset of about .1 inches.  All subsequent shots are fired in standard single action mode, where the slack on the trigger is much shorter, but the point of release feels the same.  In order to deactivate Single-Action or Anti-Stress mode, the user can manipulate the decocker button on the top of the slide, just in front of the rear sights.  When decocked from Single-Action mode, the trigger will reset to the full length of its pull.  The pistol is now in Double-Action mode with a pull 7.9 pounds for the full length of the .55 inch pull. After firing the first shot in Double-Action, the pistol will be fired in Single-Action for all subsequent shots.\n\nThe striker protrudes visibly and palpably from the back of the slide when the firearm is in a constant partially cocked state.\nIt should however be noted that the striker of the second generation P99QA variant does not protrude from the back of the slide, unless fired, as the firearm is in a constant partially cocked state.\n\nErgonomics were a key focus in the design of the firearm, and as a result, three interchangeable grip backstraps are included (small, medium and large)  to accommodate various hand shapes and sizes; this feature permits most shooters a comfortable and efficient grip on the firearm. This adaptable grip was innovative at the time the P99 was introduced.\n\nThe slide and other metal parts of the pistol are [[Tenifer]] treated (a [[nitriding]] process also used on [[Glock]] pistols). The Tenifer finish is between {{convert|0.04|mm|in|abbr=on|3}} and {{convert|0.05|mm|in|abbr=on|3}} in thickness, and is characterized by extreme resistance to wear and corrosion; it penetrates the metal, and treated parts have similar properties even below the surface to a certain depth.<ref name=\"Kasler_137\">Kasler, 137</ref> The Tenifer process produces a matte gray-colored, non-glare surface with a 64 [[Rockwell scale|Rockwell C]] hardness rating and a 99% resistance to [[seawater|salt water]] corrosion (which meets or exceeds [[stainless steel]] specifications),<ref name=\"Kokalis_321\">Kokalis, 321</ref> making the P99 particularly suitable for individuals carrying the pistol [[Concealed carry in the United States|concealed]] as the highly chloride-resistant finish allows the pistol to better endure the effects of perspiration.<ref name=\"Kasler_137\"/>\n\nThe P99 features four internal safeties, [[iron sights]] adjustable for both [[windage]] and [[elevation (ballistics)|elevation]], tool-less take down, and an [[ambidextrous]] [[magazine (firearms)|magazine]] release incorporated into the [[trigger guard]]. The lower forward edge of the frame also known as the dust cover has a mounting-bracket or [[Rail Integration System|rail interface system]] for attaching accessories, such as a [[tactical light]] or [[Laser applications#Laser sight|laser sight]].\n\nThe P99 feeds from staggered-column or double-stack [[Magazine (firearms)|magazine]]s of varying capacity. Walther also offers staggered-column magazines with a +2 baseplate that add 2 rounds to the magazine capacity at the expense of extending the grip and the pistol height by approximately {{convert|18|mm|abbr=on|1}}.\n\nThe .40 S&W caliber models incorporate a slightly larger slide in order to preserve the same recoil spring assembly used in its 9mm counterpart. The P99 is available in 4 colorations; a black frame with a black slide, a black frame with a titanium-coated slide, a military olive-drab frame with a black slide, and a desert tan frame with black slide. All three of these finishes incorporate the same black grip inserts that come with every P99. The compact versions of the P99 are only available in all black.<ref name=waltherfaq>[http://lundestudio.com/WaltherP99FAQ/ Walther P99 FAQ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212234948/http://lundestudio.com/WaltherP99FAQ/ |date=2009-02-12 }}</ref>\n\n===Accessories===\nFixed metal 3-dot iron sights, fixed [[Tritium illumination#Small arms sights|tritium]] night sights, adjustable sports iron sights, adjustable optic fibre iron sights, [[laser sight|laser pointer]]s, [[tactical light]]s, magazine flashlight adapters, holsters, magazines, magazine loaders, grip extenders and a [[suppressor]] kit with a 117&nbsp;mm (4.6&nbsp;in) barrel and protective cap for the muzzle threads and a silencer that reduces the sound signature by 33&nbsp;dB(A) are offered as factory accessories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carl-walther.de/index.php?company=walther&lang=EN&content=products&hid=9|title=Walther Defense Accessories|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Second generation variants==\n===P99AS (Anti Stress)===\n[[File:Walther P99 Left.jpg|thumb|Walther P99AS second generation pistol chambered in .40 S&W.]]\nIntroduced in 2004, this variant comes closest to a traditional Double-Action/Single-Action trigger with a decocker. In Double-Action mode the internal striker is at rest with no pre-load and the trigger travel is 14&nbsp;mm (0.55&nbsp;in) long at approximately {{convert|38|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}} trigger pull. When the slide is racked completely to the rear upon (re)loading, the internal striker is manually pre-cocked to Single-Action mode and the trigger remains in the forward position for the first shot and the Anti Stress mode is activated. The trigger travel is 14&nbsp;mm (0.55&nbsp;in) long in the Anti Stress mode at approximately {{convert|20|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}} trigger pull. On all subsequent shots, the P99AS is automatically pre-cocked and the trigger travel is reduced to 8&nbsp;mm (0.3&nbsp;in) at the same {{convert|20|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}} trigger pull. For manually deactivating the Anti Stress mode and setting the pistol to Double-Action mode the P99AS features a decock key or knob on the slide. The Anti Stress mode can also be manually activated by moving the slide approximately 10&nbsp;mm (0.4&nbsp;in) back.<ref name=\"Walther P99 flyer\">[http://www.carl-walther.de/files/pdf/P99E.pdf Walther P99 flyer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523012156/http://www.carl-walther.de/files/pdf/P99E.pdf |date=2011-05-23 }}</ref> The P99AS is still in production today.\n\n===P99DAO (Double Action Only)===\nThe P99DAO is similar to the previously produced P990 Double Action Only variant.<ref>[http://www.politieparcours.eu/PDF%20files/Sam156.pdf Het nieuwe politie pistool deel 1, SAM Wapenmagazine 156]</ref> The internal striker is at rest with no pre-load. The trigger travel is approximately 14&nbsp;mm (0.55&nbsp;in) with a trigger pull of approximately {{convert|38|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}}. The trigger pull is consistent in length and force from the first shot to the last and the striker returns to its de-cocked position after each shot.<ref name=\"Walther P99 flyer\"/>\n\n===P99QA (Quick Action)===\nThis variant has a [[Glock pistol|Glock]] style trigger system with a pre-loaded internal striker. When the trigger is pulled, the striker is fully cocked and released, firing the pistol. The trigger travel is approximately 8&nbsp;mm (0.3&nbsp;in) with a trigger pull of approximately {{convert|38|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}}. The trigger pull is consistent in length and force from the first shot to the last.<ref name=\"Walther P99 flyer\"/> The P99QA was announced in 2000 and discontinued in 2011.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\n===P99c (Compact) versions===\nCompact versions of the P99 available in the 3 preceding action types marketed as the:\n*'''P99c AS''' (Compact Anti Stress)\n*'''P99c DAO''' (Compact Double Action Only)\n*'''P99c QA''' (Compact Quick Action)\n\n===Training variant===\n====P99RAM (Real Action Marker)====\nThe P99RAM is a training and simulation pistol, equipped with a CO<sub>2</sub> blow-back system. It fires low-cost Paint- and Rubberball ammunition in caliber {{convert|.43|in|abbr=on}}. In its design, controls, and handling, the P99RAM is indistinguishable from the original P99 pistol. Protective clothing is needed to adequately protect the users from Paint- and Rubberball hits during training.\n\n===Limited editions===\nWalther has also created several limited production runs of the P99 including:\n*'''MI-6''' ([[James Bond]]) a marketing tie-in with the new James Bond movies\n*'''Year 2000''' - a limited edition P99 fabricated to commemorate the new millennium. 2000 of these were made to reciprocate the year for which it was issued.\n*'''P99 TA''' - a model prepared for the police tryouts in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] in 2002, featuring a single/double-action trigger with redesigned trigger guard, center location ambidextrous decocker and an early ambidextrous slide catch as well as the removal of the \"captured\" accessory rail in favor of a standard \"open\" rail system. Lastly, this model has new contours on the lower frame just ahead of the disassembly clasp, just before the accessory rails to facilitate holstering.<ref>Deutsches Waffen-Journal 12/2002</ref> Approximately fifty (50) P99 TAs were produced with less than 25 sold to the public (10 imported to the U.S.).{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\n===Fabryka Broni Radom P99 RAD===\n[[File:Walther P99RAD PICT0081.jpg|thumb|right|P99 RAD made by Fabryka Broni Radom.]]\n\nThe '''P99 RAD''' variant is made under license by [[\u0141ucznik Arms Factory|Fabryka Broni Radom]] in Poland and marketed as a military sidearm proposition.<ref>[http://en.fabrykabroni.pl/img/karta_ANG_RAD.pdf RAD Personal Semiautomatic Pistol] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726003122/http://en.fabrykabroni.pl/img/karta_ANG_RAD.pdf |date=2011-07-26 }}</ref>\n\nThe P99 RAD grip shape and texture has been altered when compared to the P99 variants and an extended ambidextrous slide release and extended ambidextrous magazine release levers are fitted as a standard feature. Besides that the slide shape, dimensions and serrations have been altered. The standard sights are high-contrast 3 dot sights with contrast enhancements that have been painted with afterglow paint that can aid target acquisition under unfavourable lighting conditions. As an option the P99 RAD can also be fitted with self-luminous tritium [[Iron sight#Contrast enhancements|night sights]]. The P99 RAD pistol is available with the DAO trigger mechanism with a trigger pull of approximately {{convert|39|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}} and the QA trigger mechanism with a trigger pull of approximately {{convert|32|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}}. The grip frame has an integrated mounting [[MIL-STD-1913]] (Picatinny) rail for attaching tactical lights and laser sighting devices.\n\nMany of the alterations found in the P99 RAD variant were applied in the [[Walther PPQ]] pistol introduced in 2011.\n\n===P99Q police pistol===\n[[File:Walther P99Q.jpg|thumb|P99Q police duty pistol.]]\n\nMany of the alterations found in the Fabryka Broni Radom P99 RAD variant were also applied in the Walther P99Q pistol. The P99Q is a designated police pistol, which has been certified according to the Technical Specifications (TR) of the German Police (Technische Richtlinie Pistolen im Kaliber 9mm x 19, Revision January 2008).<ref>{{in lang|de}} {{cite web|url=http://www.pfa.nrw.de/PTI_Internet/pti-intern.dhpol.local/WG/Regelungen/Pistolen/TR_01_08/TR-Pistole_31-01-08.pdf.html|title=Technische Richtlinie Pistolen im Kaliber 9mm x 19, Revision January 2008. According to the Technical Specifications (TR 2008) of the German Police for obtaining a German Police duty pistol certification a first shot trigger pull of \u2265{{convert|30|N|lb-f|1|abbr=on}}, a trigger travel of \u2265{{convert|10|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} and a trigger reset of \u2265{{convert|4|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} are required.|accessdate=24 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129023008/http://www.pfa.nrw.de/PTI_Internet/pti-intern.dhpol.local/WG/Regelungen/Pistolen/TR_01_08/TR-Pistole_31-01-08.pdf.html|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> The P99Q is exclusively manufactured for German and foreign police departments and is not available on the civilian market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carl-walther.de/cw.php?lang=en&content=portal&sub=police|title=Walther P99Q|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> The P99Q has a partially pre-loaded internal striker trigger mechanism that conforms to the Technical Specifications (TR) of the German Police. When the trigger is pulled, the striker is fully cocked and released, firing the pistol. Trigger travel is approximately {{convert|13|mm|in|1|lk=on|abbr=on}} with a trigger reset of {{convert|6|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} and a trigger pull of approximately {{convert|32|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}}. The trigger pull is consistent in length and force from the first shot to the last. The Technical Specifications (TR 2008) of the German Police also demand an accuracy of fire for a 10-shot group with German Police certified 9\u00d719mm Parabellum ammunition<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pfa.nrw.de/PTI_Internet/pti-intern.dhpol.local/WG/Regelungen/Munition/TR_Munition_mit_Anlagen1-13_09-09.pdf.html|title=Technische Richtlinie (TR) Patrone 9 mm x 19, schadstoffreduziert, Revision September 2009 |publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014|language=de}}</ref> at {{convert|25|m|yd|0|abbr=on}} (R<sub>100</sub>)<ref>R<sub>100</sub> at {{convert|25|m|yd|abbr=on|0}} means all shots of the 10-shot group will all be within a circle of the mentioned diameter at {{convert|25|m|yd|abbr=on|0}}.</ref> of \u2264 {{convert|16|cm|in|1|lk=on|abbr=on}}. This equals an accuracy of fire of \u2264 22 [[minute of angle]] (MOA) or \u2264 6.4 [[Angular mil|mrad]]. The grip frame has an integrated mounting [[MIL-STD-1913]] (Picatinny) rail for attaching tactical lights and laser sighting devices.\n\n===Smith & Wesson SW99===\n[[File:Sw99 small.jpg|thumb|right|Smith & Wesson SW99.]]\n\nThe [[Smith & Wesson SW99]] is a joint venture between Walther, who produces a modified receiver in Germany, and Smith & Wesson, who fabricates the slides and barrels in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.handgunsmag.com/reviews/featured_handguns_hg_99ers_201007/|title=The '99ers|date=2010-09-24|work=Handguns|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref> Magazines can be interchanged between the two models, but the pistols are considered to be two separate types, and are easily distinguished from each other by the trigger guard, grip and slide design. The SW99 is also available in [[.45 ACP]], while the P99 is not. The P99 was developed and introduced prior to the SW99.  Walther introduced a color-coding system to denote the difference between early generation SW99 and P99 magazines, with the latest generation being bright blue.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\nAll 9mm P99s have always been completely German-made. Some P99 .40 components are manufactured under license by S&W. The barrel, slide and frame of all 100% German-manufactured P99s bear an \"Eagle over N\" proof mark of the German Proof House at Ulm. The mark indicates the pistol was test-fired with a Proof Load; the \"N\" stands for nitrocellulose.\n\n===Magnum Research MR Eagle===\nThe [[Magnum Research]] MR Eagle was another joint American/German venture, with Walther producing a black polymer frame with integral steel rails similar to the P99 series, only differing in grip texture and with the short magazine release paddles from the first gen P99. For its part, Magnum Research Inc. produced a 416 stainless steel slide and [[41xx steel|4140 CrMo steel]] barrel in their Pillager, MN factory in the United States. The MR Eagle series pistols were available in 9\u00d719mm Parabellum (MR9) and .40 S&W (MR40).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magnumresearch.com/Firearms/Magnum-Research-MR9-Eagle-15-Round.asp|title=MR9 Eagle, 15 Round|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magnumresearch.com/Firearms/Magnum-Research-MR40-Eagle-11-Round.asp|title=MR40 Eagle, 11 Round|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Users==\n<!--READ FIRST: This section is for cited entries only. Please do not add entries into this list without a citation from a reliable source. All entries without a citation will be removed. Thank you.-->\n\n*{{flag|Canada}}: [[SPVM]] (City of Montr\u00e9al Police Service)<ref>http://www.spvm.qc.ca/upload/documentations/Bilan_SPVM_2003_angl.pdf</ref><ref>Walther Defense Catalog 2008, Page 6.</ref> and SPVQ (Service de Police de la Ville de Qu\u00e9bec), \u00c9cole nationale de police du Qu\u00e9bec, Services correctionnels Qu\u00e9bec, Constables sp\u00e9ciaux Minist\u00e8re de la s\u00e9curit\u00e9 publique. {{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n*{{flag|Estonia}}: In 2014 the [[Estonian Police]] will be armed with the P99Q, as a replacement for the currently used [[Makarov pistol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/ajakiri_radar/docs/radar_18|title=Periodic magazine \"Radar\"}}</ref> As of March 2014 the P99Q is issued to the [[Police and Border Guard Board]]<ref>[http://www.carl-walther.de/public/downloads/presse/en/Presse-Info_Polizei_Estland_EN.pdf WALTHER P99Q for Estonian Police]</ref> After just 2 years in service the Estonian Police and Border Guard have started replacing the Walther P99Q with a custom Glock 19 Gen 4 variant. This was due to [http://www.pealinn.ee/tagid/koik/politsei-vahetab-valja-alles-moni-aasta-tagasi-soetatud-pustolid-n198472 issues with the P99Q malfunctioning during training and duty use]. Up to 1000 Walther P99Q pistols are expected to remain in service during the transition period.\n*{{flag|Finland}}: Used by the [[Finnish Defence Forces]] as the '''PIST 2003''' (''Pistooli 2003'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mil.fi/maavoimat/kalustoesittely/index.dsp?level=65&equipment=170|title=PIST 2003|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> The Walther P99Q has also been chosen as the new personal handgun for [[Law enforcement in Finland|police]], customs and [[Finnish Border Guard|border guard]] personnel (7,800 pistols).<ref name=\"hbl.fi\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carl-walther.de/public/downloads/presse/en/Press_Release_Finland_Police.pdf |title=The Finland Police chooses the WALTHER P99Q |date=March 2012 |accessdate=2012-12-14}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Germany}}: 41,000 P99DAO pistols purchased in 2005 for the [[North Rhine-Westphalia Police]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3197/is_7_50/ai_n14836955 |work=Shooting Industry |title=Walther P99 selected for German Police force |year=2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225200131/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3197/is_7_50/ai_n14836955 |archivedate=2009-02-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carl-walther.info/dev2/index.php?company%3Dwalther%26lang%3DDE%26content%3Dpresse%26sub%3Darchiv |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618033001/http://www.carl-walther.info/dev2/index.php?company=walther&lang=DE&content=presse&sub=archiv |archivedate=2008-06-18 }}</ref> The [[Landespolizei|State police]] of [[Rhineland-Palatinate Police|Rhineland-Palatinate]] procured approx. 10,000 units of the P99Q. The P99Q has also been ordered by the police forces of [[Hamburg Police|Hamburg]] (8,000 pistols), [[Bremen]] (2,000 pistols) and [[Schleswig-Holstein]] (8,000 pistols) with deliveries between 2009 and 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shz.de/nachrichten/home/top-thema/article//james-bonds-dienstwaffe-fuer-polizisten-im-norden.html |title=James Bonds Dienstwaffe f\u00fcr Polizisten im Norden |access-date=2010-04-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312152708/http://www.shz.de/nachrichten/home/top-thema/article//james-bonds-dienstwaffe-fuer-polizisten-im-norden.html |archive-date=2012-03-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*{{flag|Ireland}}: [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na]]; [[Garda National Surveillance Unit|National Surveillance Unit]] (P99c), [[National Bureau of Criminal Investigation]] (P99c), [[Drugs and Organised Crime Bureau]], [[Special Detective Unit]], [[Garda Emergency Response Unit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.garda.ie/Documents/User/col_yr_bk_english.pdf|title=Garda College Yearbook listing weapons training on page 66}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Macedonia}}: Used by Special Task Unit \"Tiger\".<ref>https://specijalne-jedinice.com/Inostranstvo/Region/Jedinica-za-specijalne-zadatke-Tigrovi-Republike-Makedonije-English.html#sthash.4ZljdZ0l.dpbs</ref>\n*{{flag|Malaysia}}: [[Royal Malaysia Police]] (20,000 pistols).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.malaysiandefence.com/?p=375|title=''Whats With PDRM and Walther?''|date=2008-03-11|accessdate=2009-12-14|publisher=Malaysian Defence}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suedwest-aktiv.de/region/swp_neuulm/ulm_und_neu_ulm/3351751/artikel.php?SWAID=5f62cc42b1a437e9fcd1829bd8e2da05|title=''Gro\u00dfauftrag f\u00fcr Walther aus Malaysia''|date=2008-01-22|accessdate=2011-10-17|publisher=S\u00fcdwest Presse}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Netherlands}}: Since 2013 the [[Dutch police]] is armed with the P99Q, as a replacement for the [[Walther P5]] (45,000 pistols).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rijksoverheid.nl/nieuws/2012/10/25/nieuw-pistool-voor-nederlandse-politie.html |title=Nieuw pistool voor Nederlandse politie, www.rijksoverheid.nl (Dutch) |date=2012-10-26 |accessdate=2012-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102114501/http://www.rijksoverheid.nl/nieuws/2012/10/25/nieuw-pistool-voor-nederlandse-politie.html |archive-date=2013-11-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rijksoverheid.nl/bestanden/documenten-en-publicaties/kamerstukken/2012/10/25/brief-tweede-kamer-voorlopige-gunning-nieuw-dienstpistool-politie/voorlopige-gunning-nieuw-dienstpistool-politie2.pdf |title=Brief Tweede Kamer Voorlopige gunning nieuw dienstpistool politie, www.rijksoverheid.nl (Dutch) |date=2012-10-25 |accessdate=2012-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102114422/http://www.rijksoverheid.nl/bestanden/documenten-en-publicaties/kamerstukken/2012/10/25/brief-tweede-kamer-voorlopige-gunning-nieuw-dienstpistool-politie/voorlopige-gunning-nieuw-dienstpistool-politie2.pdf |archive-date=2013-11-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carl-walther.de/public/downloads/presse/en/Press_Release-P99Q-Dutch-EN_Gun_Magazines.pdf |title=WALTHER P99Q large-scale order from the Netherlands |date=November 2012 |accessdate=2012-12-14}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Poland}}:<ref name=\"jones2009\">Jones, Richard D. ''Jane's Infantry Weapons 2009/2010''. Jane's Information Group; 35 edition (January 27, 2009). {{ISBN|978-0-7106-2869-5}}.</ref> P99 AS/QA/DAO and domestic variant ''RAD'' are made by [[\u0141ucznik Arms Factory]].<ref>[http://www.fabrykabroni.pl/?d=114 fabrykabroni.pl]</ref> [[Policja|Police]] received around 80,000 units<ref>[http://www.altair.com.pl/news/view?news_id=10711 Kolejne P99 dla Policji (More P99 for Police).] altair.com.pl, 17 June 2013.</ref> and ordered further 3,000.<ref>[http://www.altair.com.pl/news/view?news_id=16477 Kolejne P99 dla Policji.] altair.com.pl, 18 May 2015</ref>\n*{{flag|Portugal}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv1.rtp.pt/noticias/index.php?t=Direccao-Nacional-da-PSP-garante-que-policia-que-matou-homem-tinha-formacao-de-tiro.rtp&article=328608&layout=10&visual=3&tm=|title=Direco Nacional da PSP garante que polcia que matou homem tinha formao de tiro|author=RTP, Rdio e Televiso de Portugal -  2010 LUSA - Agncia de Notcias de Portugal, S.A.|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> Pol\u00edcia de Seguran\u00e7a P\u00fablica (PSP), Autoridade de Seguran\u00e7a Alimentar e Econ\u00f3mica (ASAE), Grupo de Interven\u00e7\u00e3o e Opera\u00e7\u00f5es Especiais da GNR (GNR/GIOE)\n*[[Peshmerga]]: over 2000 polish P99 have been issued to Army and police units.\n*{{flag|Serbia}}: Used by the Special Forces of Police.<ref>[http://specijalne-jedinice.com/Oprema/Pistolji/Walther-P99.html#sthash.c4OT20ff.dpbs]</ref><ref>http://specijalne-jedinice.com/img/dummies/WALTERP99Q/11.jpg</ref>\n*{{flag|Spain}}: [[Barcelona]] Municipal Police carry the Walther P99\n*{{flag|Turkey}}: Standart issue sidearm of [[Turkish Armed Forces]] and [[General Directorate of Security]].<ref>https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/turkiye/guvenlik-gucleri-yerli-tabanca-meteyle-kusaniyor/1766628</ref> Produced by [[Canik Arms]], labeled as '''Canik TP9'''.<ref>http://www.trthaber.com/haber/gundem/iste-turk-polisinin-yeni-silahi-98423.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tactical-life.com/combat-handguns/century%E2%80%99s-canik55-tp-9/|title=Century\u2019s CANIK55 TP-9 Pistol Review|work=Tactical Life|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> The TP9 is imported to the United States by [[Century International Arms|Century Arms International]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.thetruthaboutguns.com/2012/12/james-grant/gun-review-cai-canik55-tp-9/|title = Gun Review: CAI Canik TP-9|date = December 22, 2012|accessdate = December 3, 2015|website = The Truth About Guns|publisher = |last = Grant|first = James}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Ukraine}}: [[Security Service of Ukraine|SBU]]<ref>\"''\u041f\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043c\u043e \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u044f, \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432\u043e \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420, \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u0442 \u043f\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u044b... '''Walther P99'''''\"<br/>\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439. [http://www.bratishka.ru/archiv/2009/6/2009_6_7.php \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044b: \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u00ab\u0410\u043b\u044c\u0444\u0430\u00bb: \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043c \u043d\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0435\u0442] // \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0448\u043a\u0430\", \u0438\u044e\u043d\u044c 2009</ref>\n*{{flag|United Kingdom}}: [[Nottinghamshire Police]] armed specialist units used the P99DAO.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freiwilliger-polizeidienst.de/Infothek/Meinungen_und_Ansichten/Armed_Officers_in_UK/armed_officers_in_uk.html|title=Nottinghamshire Police use P990DAO}}</ref> In 2016 the units switched to the [[Glock#9.C3.9719mm Parabellum|Glock 17]] pistol.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Walther P99-JH02.jpg|P99QA field stripped to its main parts\nImage:WALTHER P99TA.jpg|P99 TA with laser unit and flash suppressor\nFile:Walther P99c AS PICT0024.jpg|Polish made P99c AS\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Walther P22]], a rimfire pistol possessing similar styling and ergonomics chambered in [[.22 LR]].\n*[[Walther PK380]], a centerfire pistol also possessing similar styling and ergonomics with an overall size between the P22 and P99, but chambered in [[.380 ACP]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Walther P99}}\n*[http://www.waltherarms.com/handguns/p99/ P99 Semi-Automatic Pistols] at Carl Walther Sportwaffen GmbH\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100613041019/http://www.carl-walther.de/downloads/Defense-Katalog-2008-DE-EN.pdf Walther 2008 Defense Catalog]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130319063410/http://www.waltherarms.com/resources/manuals/279%2093%2016%20a%20Instruction%20Manual%20P99.pdf P99 Manual]\n*[http://www.waltherarms.com/products/handguns/p99/ Walther Arms P99]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040314102751/http://www.gunfaqs.org/P99FAQ/index.html Walther P99 FAQ \"Lenaburg Edition\"]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111117000919/http://lundestudio.com/WaltherP99FAQ/index.html Ken Lunde's SIG Pro FAQ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100914213257/http://world.guns.ru/handguns/hg14-e.htm Walther P99 at World Guns]\n*[http://www.waltherforums.com/ Walther Forums]\n\n{{Walther}}\n\n[[Category:.40 S&W semi-automatic pistols]]\n[[Category:9\u00d721mm IMI semi-automatic pistols]]\n[[Category:9mm Parabellum semi-automatic pistols]]\n[[Category:Police weapons]]\n[[Category:Post\u2013Cold War weapons of Germany]]\n[[Category:Short recoil firearms]]\n[[Category:Walther semi-automatic pistols|P99]]\n[[Category:Weapons and ammunition introduced in 1996]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the semi-automatic pistol||P99 (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name=Walther P99\n| image= Walther P99 9x19mm.png\n| image_size = 300\n|caption=A first-generation 9mm version, with a green polymer frame.\n|origin=Germany\n|type=[[Semi-automatic pistol]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged=yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n|service=1997-present\n|used_by=See ''[[Walther P99#Users|Users]]''\n<!-- Production history -->\n|designer=Horst Wesp\n|design_date=1994\u20131996\n|manufacturer=[[Walther arms|Carl Walther GmbH Sportwaffen]]\n|production_date=1997\u2013present\n|number=\n|variants=P99QPQ, P99 Military, P990 (P99DAO), P99QA, P99QNL, P99AS, P99TA, P99C, P99C AS, P99C QA, P99C DAO, P99 RAD, P99Q and [[Smith & Wesson SW99|SW99]]\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight={{convert|630|g|oz|abbr=on}} (9\u00d719mm)<br/>{{convert|655|g|abbr=on}} (.40 S&W)\n|length={{convert|180|mm|in|abbr=on}} (9\u00d719mm)<br/> {{convert|184|mm|abbr=on|1}} (.40 S&W)\n|part_length={{convert|102|mm|abbr=on|1}} (9\u00d719mm)<br/> {{convert|106|mm|abbr=on|1}} (.40 S&W)\n|width={{convert|29|mm|abbr=on|1}} (9\u00d719mm)<br/>{{convert|32|mm|abbr=on|1}} (.40 S&W)\n|height={{convert|135|mm|abbr=on|1}}\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n|cartridge=[[9\u00d719mm Parabellum]]<br/> [[.40 S&W]]<br/> [[9\u00d721mm IMI]]\n|action=[[Recoil operation|Short recoil operated]], locked breech\n|range={{convert|50|m|yd|abbr=on}} (9\u00d719mm)\n|velocity={{convert|408|m/s|0|abbr=on}} (9\u00d719mm) <br/> {{convert|344|m/s|abbr=on|0}} (.40 S&W)\n|feed=9\u00d719mm: 10-, 15-, 17- or 20-round detachable [[box magazine]]<br/> .40 S&W: 10-, 12-, or 14-round box magazine\n|sights=Interchangeable 3-dot notch sight\n}}\n\nThe '''Walther P99''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8valt\u0250|lang}}) is a [[semi-automatic pistol]] developed by the German company [[Walther arms|Carl Walther GmbH Sportwaffen]] of [[Ulm]] for law enforcement, security forces and the civilian shooting market as a replacement for the [[Walther P5]] and the [[Walther P88|P88]]. The P99 and its variants are also made under licence by [[\u0141ucznik Arms Factory|Fabryka Broni Radom]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.fabrykabroni.pl/?d=114|title=P99 Personal Semiautomatic Pistol|accessdate=2010-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204045656/http://en.fabrykabroni.pl/?d=114|archive-date=2010-02-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDesign work on this new generation sidearm began in 1994, and the handgun was presented in 1997 with series production commencing that same year.<ref name=\"Walther P99 at World Guns\">{{cite web|url=http://world.guns.ru/handguns/hg14-e.htm|title=Walther P99 at World Guns|accessdate=24 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914213257/http://world.guns.ru/handguns/hg14-e.htm|archive-date=2010-09-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> The weapon was first introduced chambered in [[9\u00d719mm Parabellum]].\n\nThe pistol is used by the [[Landespolizei|German Police]] in [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] and [[Rhineland-Palatinate]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dienstwaffen.di.funpic.de/herstellerwxyz/walther/5119799b3208d9102.html|title=P 99 Q|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426010701/http://dienstwaffen.di.funpic.de/herstellerwxyz/walther/5119799b3208d9102.html|archive-date=2012-04-26|url-status=|access-date=2018-09-15}}</ref> and has been ordered by [[Bremen]], [[Hamburg]] and [[Schleswig-Holstein]], the [[Law enforcement in Poland|Polish Police]] and the [[Finnish Army]]'s special forces and military police, where it carries the designation '''PIST 2003''' (''Pistooli 2003'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mil.fi/maavoimat/kalustoesittely/index.dsp?level=65&equipment=170|title=Finnish Army equipment page PIST 2003|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> The Walther P99Q was also chosen in 2012 to replace older pistols and revolvers of the Finnish Police, Customs and Border Guard. This gun has also been chosen to replace the [[Walther P5]] of the Dutch Police in 2013.<ref name=\"hbl.fi\">{{cite web|url=http://hbl.fi/nyheter/2012-01-18/polisens-nya-tjanstevapen-kommer-fran-tyskland|title=hbl.fi|work=Hbl.fi - Finlands ledande nyhetssajt p\u00e5 svenska|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> In 2014 the Walther P99Q was also chosen to replace the [[Makarov PM]] of the [[Estonian Police]] and Border Guard Board.\n\n==Product evolution==\nThe Walther P99 was modified several times throughout its production history, as were the magazines. When the P99 was introduced the magazine capacities were 16 rounds for 9\u00d719mm Parabellum and 12 rounds for .40 S&W. Magazines had witness holes on both sides. Later the magazine capacities were reduced to 15 rounds for 9\u00d719mm Parabellum and 11 rounds for .40 S&W while witness holes were introduced at the rear of the magazine to view the loading condition.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130417210026/http://www.lundestudio.com/WaltherP99FAQ/III/6.html Are pre-ban full-capacity magazines available for the P99? at lundestudio.com WaltherP99 FAQ via Wayback Machine]</ref>\n\n===Second generation models===\nWalther presented a redesigned second generation P99 in 2004, incorporating a modified trigger guard that eliminated the \"ski hump\", which is clearly visible in the accompanying first generation images. This was done to address user comfort concerns regarding the previous style.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.all4shooters.com/en/Shooting/pistols/Walther-P99-20-years-tested-models/|title=20 Years of the Walther P99. The top models tested - Walther - Pistols - Article - all4shooters.com|last=GmbH|first=Hamza Malalla and Matthias S. Recktenwald. Photos: Michael Schippers, Heinz D. Kupsch, Carl Walther|website=all4shooters.com (EN)|language=en|access-date=2018-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://improb.com/walther-p99/|title=Walther P99 {{!}} Improb|date=2017-10-09|work=Improb|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref> The first generation P99 pistols had a slide release at the left side of the frame while second generation guns may have optional ambidextrous slide stop release levers. Walther also took the opportunity to redesign the slide so the user could grip it more easily, and notably, change the proprietary accessory rail to a [[Weaver rail mount|Weaver]] type.\nSome models built in 2005 and all later models received one more design change, an elongated magazine release.<ref name=\"Walther P99 at World Guns\"/>\n\n==Design details==\n[[File:WP99 3.jpg|thumb|left|Walther P99 with the slide locked back displaying its vertical barrel tilt.]]\n\nThe Walther P99 is a [[Recoil operation#Short recoil operation|short recoil]]-operated locked breech [[semi-automatic pistol]] that uses a modified [[John Browning|Browning]] cam-lock system adapted from the [[Browning Hi-Power|Hi-Power]] pistol. The P99 has a glassfiber-reinforced polymer frame and steel slide assembly. It can be broken down into its main parts or field stripped with a take down catch without the help of tools.\n\nIt uses an internal [[Trigger (firearms)#Pre-set .28striker or hammer.29|striker]] as opposed to an external [[hammer (firearms)|hammer]], with a red-painted striker tip that protrudes from rear of the [[pistol slide|slide]] when the gun is cocked, as well as a [[loaded chamber indicator]] on the right side of the slide.\n\nThe original, first-generation P99 had a traditional [[Trigger (firearms)#Double-action.2Fsingle-action|Double-Action/Single-Action trigger]] with a [[De-cocker#Decocker|decocker]]. When the slide is racked completely to the rear upon loading, the trigger remains in the forward position for the first shot and the Anti-Stress mode is activated, where the striker is cocked but the trigger has the length of pull of the double-action mode. The trigger travel is 14&nbsp;mm (0.55&nbsp;in) long in the Anti-Stress mode, but the most of the length is slack and is similar in feel to a two-stage rifle trigger. At the end of the anti-stress travel, the pressure noticeably increases to 4.5 pounds and the user experiences a crisp trigger break and an extremely short trigger reset of about .1 inches.  All subsequent shots are fired in standard single action mode, where the slack on the trigger is much shorter, but the point of release feels the same.  In order to deactivate Single-Action or Anti-Stress mode, the user can manipulate the decocker button on the top of the slide, just in front of the rear sights.  When decocked from Single-Action mode, the trigger will reset to the full length of its pull.  The pistol is now in Double-Action mode with a pull 7.9 pounds for the full length of the .55 inch pull. After firing the first shot in Double-Action, the pistol will be fired in Single-Action for all subsequent shots.\n\nThe striker protrudes visibly and palpably from the back of the slide when the firearm is in a constant partially cocked state.\nIt should however be noted that the striker of the second generation P99QA variant does not protrude from the back of the slide, unless fired, as the firearm is in a constant partially cocked state.\n\nErgonomics were a key focus in the design of the firearm, and as a result, three interchangeable grip backstraps are included (small, medium and large)  to accommodate various hand shapes and sizes; this feature permits most shooters a comfortable and efficient grip on the firearm. This adaptable grip was innovative at the time the P99 was introduced.\n\nThe slide and other metal parts of the pistol are [[Tenifer]] treated (a [[nitriding]] process also used on [[Glock]] pistols). The Tenifer finish is between {{convert|0.04|mm|in|abbr=on|3}} and {{convert|0.05|mm|in|abbr=on|3}} in thickness, and is characterized by extreme resistance to wear and corrosion; it penetrates the metal, and treated parts have similar properties even below the surface to a certain depth.<ref name=\"Kasler_137\">Kasler, 137</ref> The Tenifer process produces a matte gray-colored, non-glare surface with a 64 [[Rockwell scale|Rockwell C]] hardness rating and a 99% resistance to [[seawater|salt water]] corrosion (which meets or exceeds [[stainless steel]] specifications),<ref name=\"Kokalis_321\">Kokalis, 321</ref> making the P99 particularly suitable for individuals carrying the pistol [[Concealed carry in the United States|concealed]] as the highly chloride-resistant finish allows the pistol to better endure the effects of perspiration.<ref name=\"Kasler_137\"/>\n\nThe P99 features four internal safeties, [[iron sights]] adjustable for both [[windage]] and [[elevation (ballistics)|elevation]], tool-less take down, and an [[ambidextrous]] [[magazine (firearms)|magazine]] release incorporated into the [[trigger guard]]. The lower forward edge of the frame also known as the dust cover has a mounting-bracket or [[Rail Integration System|rail interface system]] for attaching accessories, such as a [[tactical light]] or [[Laser applications#Laser sight|laser sight]].\n\nThe P99 feeds from staggered-column or double-stack [[Magazine (firearms)|magazine]]s of varying capacity. Walther also offers staggered-column magazines with a +2 baseplate that add 2 rounds to the magazine capacity at the expense of extending the grip and the pistol height by approximately {{convert|18|mm|abbr=on|1}}.\n\nThe .40 S&W caliber models incorporate a slightly larger slide in order to preserve the same recoil spring assembly used in its 9mm counterpart. The P99 is available in 4 colorations; a black frame with a black slide, a black frame with a titanium-coated slide, a military olive-drab frame with a black slide, and a desert tan frame with black slide. All three of these finishes incorporate the same black grip inserts that come with every P99. The compact versions of the P99 are only available in all black.<ref name=waltherfaq>[http://lundestudio.com/WaltherP99FAQ/ Walther P99 FAQ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212234948/http://lundestudio.com/WaltherP99FAQ/ |date=2009-02-12 }}</ref>\n\n===Accessories===\nFixed metal 3-dot iron sights, fixed [[Tritium illumination#Small arms sights|tritium]] night sights, adjustable sports iron sights, adjustable optic fibre iron sights, [[laser sight|laser pointer]]s, [[tactical light]]s, magazine flashlight adapters, holsters, magazines, magazine loaders, grip extenders and a [[suppressor]] kit with a 117&nbsp;mm (4.6&nbsp;in) barrel and protective cap for the muzzle threads and a silencer that reduces the sound signature by 33&nbsp;dB(A) are offered as factory accessories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carl-walther.de/index.php?company=walther&lang=EN&content=products&hid=9|title=Walther Defense Accessories|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Second generation variants==\n===P99AS (Anti Stress)===\n[[File:Walther P99 Left.jpg|thumb|Walther P99AS second generation pistol chambered in .40 S&W.]]\nIntroduced in 2004, this variant comes closest to a traditional Double-Action/Single-Action trigger with a decocker. In Double-Action mode the internal striker is at rest with no pre-load and the trigger travel is 14&nbsp;mm (0.55&nbsp;in) long at approximately {{convert|38|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}} trigger pull. When the slide is racked completely to the rear upon (re)loading, the internal striker is manually pre-cocked to Single-Action mode and the trigger remains in the forward position for the first shot and the Anti Stress mode is activated. The trigger travel is 14&nbsp;mm (0.55&nbsp;in) long in the Anti Stress mode at approximately {{convert|20|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}} trigger pull. On all subsequent shots, the P99AS is automatically pre-cocked and the trigger travel is reduced to 8&nbsp;mm (0.3&nbsp;in) at the same {{convert|20|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}} trigger pull. For manually deactivating the Anti Stress mode and setting the pistol to Double-Action mode the P99AS features a decock key or knob on the slide. The Anti Stress mode can also be manually activated by moving the slide approximately 10&nbsp;mm (0.4&nbsp;in) back.<ref name=\"Walther P99 flyer\">[http://www.carl-walther.de/files/pdf/P99E.pdf Walther P99 flyer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523012156/http://www.carl-walther.de/files/pdf/P99E.pdf |date=2011-05-23 }}</ref> The P99AS is still in production today.\n\n===P99DAO (Double Action Only)===\nThe P99DAO is similar to the previously produced P990 Double Action Only variant.<ref>[http://www.politieparcours.eu/PDF%20files/Sam156.pdf Het nieuwe politie pistool deel 1, SAM Wapenmagazine 156]</ref> The internal striker is at rest with no pre-load. The trigger travel is approximately 14&nbsp;mm (0.55&nbsp;in) with a trigger pull of approximately {{convert|38|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}}. The trigger pull is consistent in length and force from the first shot to the last and the striker returns to its de-cocked position after each shot.<ref name=\"Walther P99 flyer\"/>\n\n===P99QA (Quick Action)===\nThis variant has a [[Glock pistol|Glock]] style trigger system with a pre-loaded internal striker. When the trigger is pulled, the striker is fully cocked and released, firing the pistol. The trigger travel is approximately 8&nbsp;mm (0.3&nbsp;in) with a trigger pull of approximately {{convert|38|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}}. The trigger pull is consistent in length and force from the first shot to the last.<ref name=\"Walther P99 flyer\"/> The P99QA was announced in 2000 and discontinued in 2011.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\n===P99c (Compact) versions===\nCompact versions of the P99 available in the 3 preceding action types marketed as the:\n*'''P99c AS''' (Compact Anti Stress)\n*'''P99c DAO''' (Compact Double Action Only)\n*'''P99c QA''' (Compact Quick Action)\n\n===Training variant===\n====P99RAM (Real Action Marker)====\nThe P99RAM is a training and simulation pistol, equipped with a CO<sub>2</sub> blow-back system. It fires low-cost Paint- and Rubberball ammunition in caliber {{convert|.43|in|abbr=on}}. In its design, controls, and handling, the P99RAM is indistinguishable from the original P99 pistol. Protective clothing is needed to adequately protect the users from Paint- and Rubberball hits during training.\n\n===Limited editions===\nWalther has also created several limited production runs of the P99 including:\n*'''MI-6''' ([[James Bond]]) a marketing tie-in with the new James Bond movies\n*'''Year 2000''' - a limited edition P99 fabricated to commemorate the new millennium. 2000 of these were made to reciprocate the year for which it was issued.\n*'''P99 TA''' - a model prepared for the police tryouts in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] in 2002, featuring a single/double-action trigger with redesigned trigger guard, center location ambidextrous decocker and an early ambidextrous slide catch as well as the removal of the \"captured\" accessory rail in favor of a standard \"open\" rail system. Lastly, this model has new contours on the lower frame just ahead of the disassembly clasp, just before the accessory rails to facilitate holstering.<ref>Deutsches Waffen-Journal 12/2002</ref> Approximately fifty (50) P99 TAs were produced with less than 25 sold to the public (10 imported to the U.S.).{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\n===Fabryka Broni Radom P99 RAD===\n[[File:Walther P99RAD PICT0081.jpg|thumb|right|P99 RAD made by Fabryka Broni Radom.]]\n\nThe '''P99 RAD''' variant is made under license by [[\u0141ucznik Arms Factory|Fabryka Broni Radom]] in Poland and marketed as a military sidearm proposition.<ref>[http://en.fabrykabroni.pl/img/karta_ANG_RAD.pdf RAD Personal Semiautomatic Pistol] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726003122/http://en.fabrykabroni.pl/img/karta_ANG_RAD.pdf |date=2011-07-26 }}</ref>\n\nThe P99 RAD grip shape and texture has been altered when compared to the P99 variants and an extended ambidextrous slide release and extended ambidextrous magazine release levers are fitted as a standard feature. Besides that the slide shape, dimensions and serrations have been altered. The standard sights are high-contrast 3 dot sights with contrast enhancements that have been painted with afterglow paint that can aid target acquisition under unfavourable lighting conditions. As an option the P99 RAD can also be fitted with self-luminous tritium [[Iron sight#Contrast enhancements|night sights]]. The P99 RAD pistol is available with the DAO trigger mechanism with a trigger pull of approximately {{convert|39|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}} and the QA trigger mechanism with a trigger pull of approximately {{convert|32|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}}. The grip frame has an integrated mounting [[MIL-STD-1913]] (Picatinny) rail for attaching tactical lights and laser sighting devices.\n\nMany of the alterations found in the P99 RAD variant were applied in the [[Walther PPQ]] pistol introduced in 2011.\n\n===P99Q police pistol===\n[[File:Walther P99Q.jpg|thumb|P99Q police duty pistol.]]\n\nMany of the alterations found in the Fabryka Broni Radom P99 RAD variant were also applied in the Walther P99Q pistol. The P99Q is a designated police pistol, which has been certified according to the Technical Specifications (TR) of the German Police (Technische Richtlinie Pistolen im Kaliber 9mm x 19, Revision January 2008).<ref>{{in lang|de}} {{cite web|url=http://www.pfa.nrw.de/PTI_Internet/pti-intern.dhpol.local/WG/Regelungen/Pistolen/TR_01_08/TR-Pistole_31-01-08.pdf.html|title=Technische Richtlinie Pistolen im Kaliber 9mm x 19, Revision January 2008. According to the Technical Specifications (TR 2008) of the German Police for obtaining a German Police duty pistol certification a first shot trigger pull of \u2265{{convert|30|N|lb-f|1|abbr=on}}, a trigger travel of \u2265{{convert|10|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} and a trigger reset of \u2265{{convert|4|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} are required.|accessdate=24 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129023008/http://www.pfa.nrw.de/PTI_Internet/pti-intern.dhpol.local/WG/Regelungen/Pistolen/TR_01_08/TR-Pistole_31-01-08.pdf.html|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> The P99Q is exclusively manufactured for German and foreign police departments and is not available on the civilian market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carl-walther.de/cw.php?lang=en&content=portal&sub=police|title=Walther P99Q|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> The P99Q has a partially pre-loaded internal striker trigger mechanism that conforms to the Technical Specifications (TR) of the German Police. When the trigger is pulled, the striker is fully cocked and released, firing the pistol. Trigger travel is approximately {{convert|13|mm|in|1|lk=on|abbr=on}} with a trigger reset of {{convert|6|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} and a trigger pull of approximately {{convert|32|N|lb-f|1|lk=on|abbr=on}}. The trigger pull is consistent in length and force from the first shot to the last. The Technical Specifications (TR 2008) of the German Police also demand an accuracy of fire for a 10-shot group with German Police certified 9\u00d719mm Parabellum ammunition<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pfa.nrw.de/PTI_Internet/pti-intern.dhpol.local/WG/Regelungen/Munition/TR_Munition_mit_Anlagen1-13_09-09.pdf.html|title=Technische Richtlinie (TR) Patrone 9 mm x 19, schadstoffreduziert, Revision September 2009 |publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014|language=de}}</ref> at {{convert|25|m|yd|0|abbr=on}} (R<sub>100</sub>)<ref>R<sub>100</sub> at {{convert|25|m|yd|abbr=on|0}} means all shots of the 10-shot group will all be within a circle of the mentioned diameter at {{convert|25|m|yd|abbr=on|0}}.</ref> of \u2264 {{convert|16|cm|in|1|lk=on|abbr=on}}. This equals an accuracy of fire of \u2264 22 [[minute of angle]] (MOA) or \u2264 6.4 [[Angular mil|mrad]]. The grip frame has an integrated mounting [[MIL-STD-1913]] (Picatinny) rail for attaching tactical lights and laser sighting devices.\n\n===Smith & Wesson SW99===\n[[File:Sw99 small.jpg|thumb|right|Smith & Wesson SW99.]]\n\nThe [[Smith & Wesson SW99]] is a joint venture between Walther, who produces a modified receiver in Germany, and Smith & Wesson, who fabricates the slides and barrels in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.handgunsmag.com/reviews/featured_handguns_hg_99ers_201007/|title=The '99ers|date=2010-09-24|work=Handguns|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref> Magazines can be interchanged between the two models, but the pistols are considered to be two separate types, and are easily distinguished from each other by the trigger guard, grip and slide design. The SW99 is also available in [[.45 ACP]], while the P99 is not. The P99 was developed and introduced prior to the SW99.  Walther introduced a color-coding system to denote the difference between early generation SW99 and P99 magazines, with the latest generation being bright blue.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\nAll 9mm P99s have always been completely German-made. Some P99 .40 components are manufactured under license by S&W. The barrel, slide and frame of all 100% German-manufactured P99s bear an \"Eagle over N\" proof mark of the German Proof House at Ulm. The mark indicates the pistol was test-fired with a Proof Load; the \"N\" stands for nitrocellulose.\n\n===Magnum Research MR Eagle===\nThe [[Magnum Research]] MR Eagle was another joint American/German venture, with Walther producing a black polymer frame with integral steel rails similar to the P99 series, only differing in grip texture and with the short magazine release paddles from the first gen P99. For its part, Magnum Research Inc. produced a 416 stainless steel slide and [[41xx steel|4140 CrMo steel]] barrel in their Pillager, MN factory in the United States. The MR Eagle series pistols were available in 9\u00d719mm Parabellum (MR9) and .40 S&W (MR40).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magnumresearch.com/Firearms/Magnum-Research-MR9-Eagle-15-Round.asp|title=MR9 Eagle, 15 Round|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magnumresearch.com/Firearms/Magnum-Research-MR40-Eagle-11-Round.asp|title=MR40 Eagle, 11 Round|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Users==\n<!--READ FIRST: This section is for cited entries only. Please do not add entries into this list without a citation from a reliable source. All entries without a citation will be removed. Thank you.-->\n\n*{{flag|Canada}}: [[SPVM]] (City of Montr\u00e9al Police Service)<ref>http://www.spvm.qc.ca/upload/documentations/Bilan_SPVM_2003_angl.pdf</ref><ref>Walther Defense Catalog 2008, Page 6.</ref> and SPVQ (Service de Police de la Ville de Qu\u00e9bec), \u00c9cole nationale de police du Qu\u00e9bec, Services correctionnels Qu\u00e9bec, Constables sp\u00e9ciaux Minist\u00e8re de la s\u00e9curit\u00e9 publique. {{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n*{{flag|Estonia}}: In 2014 the [[Estonian Police]] will be armed with the P99Q, as a replacement for the currently used [[Makarov pistol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/ajakiri_radar/docs/radar_18|title=Periodic magazine \"Radar\"}}</ref> As of March 2014 the P99Q is issued to the [[Police and Border Guard Board]]<ref>[http://www.carl-walther.de/public/downloads/presse/en/Presse-Info_Polizei_Estland_EN.pdf WALTHER P99Q for Estonian Police]</ref> After just 2 years in service the Estonian Police and Border Guard have started replacing the Walther P99Q with a custom Glock 19 Gen 4 variant. This was due to [http://www.pealinn.ee/tagid/koik/politsei-vahetab-valja-alles-moni-aasta-tagasi-soetatud-pustolid-n198472 issues with the P99Q malfunctioning during training and duty use]. Up to 1000 Walther P99Q pistols are expected to remain in service during the transition period.\n*{{flag|Finland}}: Used by the [[Finnish Defence Forces]] as the '''PIST 2003''' (''Pistooli 2003'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mil.fi/maavoimat/kalustoesittely/index.dsp?level=65&equipment=170|title=PIST 2003|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> The Walther P99Q has also been chosen as the new personal handgun for [[Law enforcement in Finland|police]], customs and [[Finnish Border Guard|border guard]] personnel (7,800 pistols).<ref name=\"hbl.fi\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carl-walther.de/public/downloads/presse/en/Press_Release_Finland_Police.pdf |title=The Finland Police chooses the WALTHER P99Q |date=March 2012 |accessdate=2012-12-14}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Germany}}: 41,000 P99DAO pistols purchased in 2005 for the [[North Rhine-Westphalia Police]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3197/is_7_50/ai_n14836955 |work=Shooting Industry |title=Walther P99 selected for German Police force |year=2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225200131/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3197/is_7_50/ai_n14836955 |archivedate=2009-02-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carl-walther.info/dev2/index.php?company%3Dwalther%26lang%3DDE%26content%3Dpresse%26sub%3Darchiv |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618033001/http://www.carl-walther.info/dev2/index.php?company=walther&lang=DE&content=presse&sub=archiv |archivedate=2008-06-18 }}</ref> The [[Landespolizei|State police]] of [[Rhineland-Palatinate Police|Rhineland-Palatinate]] procured approx. 10,000 units of the P99Q. The P99Q has also been ordered by the police forces of [[Hamburg Police|Hamburg]] (8,000 pistols), [[Bremen]] (2,000 pistols) and [[Schleswig-Holstein]] (8,000 pistols) with deliveries between 2009 and 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shz.de/nachrichten/home/top-thema/article//james-bonds-dienstwaffe-fuer-polizisten-im-norden.html |title=James Bonds Dienstwaffe f\u00fcr Polizisten im Norden |access-date=2010-04-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312152708/http://www.shz.de/nachrichten/home/top-thema/article//james-bonds-dienstwaffe-fuer-polizisten-im-norden.html |archive-date=2012-03-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*{{flag|Ireland}}: [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na]]; [[Garda National Surveillance Unit|National Surveillance Unit]] (P99c), [[National Bureau of Criminal Investigation]] (P99c), [[Drugs and Organised Crime Bureau]], [[Special Detective Unit]], [[Garda Emergency Response Unit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.garda.ie/Documents/User/col_yr_bk_english.pdf|title=Garda College Yearbook listing weapons training on page 66}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Macedonia}}: Used by Special Task Unit \"Tiger\".<ref>https://specijalne-jedinice.com/Inostranstvo/Region/Jedinica-za-specijalne-zadatke-Tigrovi-Republike-Makedonije-English.html#sthash.4ZljdZ0l.dpbs</ref>\n*{{flag|Malaysia}}: [[Royal Malaysia Police]] (20,000 pistols).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.malaysiandefence.com/?p=375|title=''Whats With PDRM and Walther?''|date=2008-03-11|accessdate=2009-12-14|publisher=Malaysian Defence}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suedwest-aktiv.de/region/swp_neuulm/ulm_und_neu_ulm/3351751/artikel.php?SWAID=5f62cc42b1a437e9fcd1829bd8e2da05|title=''Gro\u00dfauftrag f\u00fcr Walther aus Malaysia''|date=2008-01-22|accessdate=2011-10-17|publisher=S\u00fcdwest Presse}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Netherlands}}: Since 2013 the [[Dutch police]] is armed with the P99Q, as a replacement for the [[Walther P5]] (45,000 pistols).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rijksoverheid.nl/nieuws/2012/10/25/nieuw-pistool-voor-nederlandse-politie.html |title=Nieuw pistool voor Nederlandse politie, www.rijksoverheid.nl (Dutch) |date=2012-10-26 |accessdate=2012-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102114501/http://www.rijksoverheid.nl/nieuws/2012/10/25/nieuw-pistool-voor-nederlandse-politie.html |archive-date=2013-11-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rijksoverheid.nl/bestanden/documenten-en-publicaties/kamerstukken/2012/10/25/brief-tweede-kamer-voorlopige-gunning-nieuw-dienstpistool-politie/voorlopige-gunning-nieuw-dienstpistool-politie2.pdf |title=Brief Tweede Kamer Voorlopige gunning nieuw dienstpistool politie, www.rijksoverheid.nl (Dutch) |date=2012-10-25 |accessdate=2012-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102114422/http://www.rijksoverheid.nl/bestanden/documenten-en-publicaties/kamerstukken/2012/10/25/brief-tweede-kamer-voorlopige-gunning-nieuw-dienstpistool-politie/voorlopige-gunning-nieuw-dienstpistool-politie2.pdf |archive-date=2013-11-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carl-walther.de/public/downloads/presse/en/Press_Release-P99Q-Dutch-EN_Gun_Magazines.pdf |title=WALTHER P99Q large-scale order from the Netherlands |date=November 2012 |accessdate=2012-12-14}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Poland}}:<ref name=\"jones2009\">Jones, Richard D. ''Jane's Infantry Weapons 2009/2010''. Jane's Information Group; 35 edition (January 27, 2009). {{ISBN|978-0-7106-2869-5}}.</ref> P99 AS/QA/DAO and domestic variant ''RAD'' are made by [[\u0141ucznik Arms Factory]].<ref>[http://www.fabrykabroni.pl/?d=114 fabrykabroni.pl]</ref> [[Policja|Police]] received around 80,000 units<ref>[http://www.altair.com.pl/news/view?news_id=10711 Kolejne P99 dla Policji (More P99 for Police).] altair.com.pl, 17 June 2013.</ref> and ordered further 3,000.<ref>[http://www.altair.com.pl/news/view?news_id=16477 Kolejne P99 dla Policji.] altair.com.pl, 18 May 2015</ref>\n*{{flag|Portugal}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv1.rtp.pt/noticias/index.php?t=Direccao-Nacional-da-PSP-garante-que-policia-que-matou-homem-tinha-formacao-de-tiro.rtp&article=328608&layout=10&visual=3&tm=|title=Direco Nacional da PSP garante que polcia que matou homem tinha formao de tiro|author=RTP, Rdio e Televiso de Portugal -  2010 LUSA - Agncia de Notcias de Portugal, S.A.|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> Pol\u00edcia de Seguran\u00e7a P\u00fablica (PSP), Autoridade de Seguran\u00e7a Alimentar e Econ\u00f3mica (ASAE), Grupo de Interven\u00e7\u00e3o e Opera\u00e7\u00f5es Especiais da GNR (GNR/GIOE)\n*[[Peshmerga]]: over 2000 polish P99 have been issued to Army and police units.\n*{{flag|Serbia}}: Used by the Special Forces of Police.<ref>[http://specijalne-jedinice.com/Oprema/Pistolji/Walther-P99.html#sthash.c4OT20ff.dpbs]</ref><ref>http://specijalne-jedinice.com/img/dummies/WALTERP99Q/11.jpg</ref>\n*{{flag|Spain}}: [[Barcelona]] Municipal Police carry the Walther P99\n*{{flag|Turkey}}: Standart issue sidearm of [[Turkish Armed Forces]] and [[General Directorate of Security]].<ref>https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/turkiye/guvenlik-gucleri-yerli-tabanca-meteyle-kusaniyor/1766628</ref> Produced by [[Canik Arms]], labeled as '''Canik TP9'''.<ref>http://www.trthaber.com/haber/gundem/iste-turk-polisinin-yeni-silahi-98423.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tactical-life.com/combat-handguns/century%E2%80%99s-canik55-tp-9/|title=Century\u2019s CANIK55 TP-9 Pistol Review|work=Tactical Life|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> The TP9 is imported to the United States by [[Century International Arms|Century Arms International]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.thetruthaboutguns.com/2012/12/james-grant/gun-review-cai-canik55-tp-9/|title = Gun Review: CAI Canik TP-9|date = December 22, 2012|accessdate = December 3, 2015|website = The Truth About Guns|publisher = |last = Grant|first = James}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Ukraine}}: [[Security Service of Ukraine|SBU]]<ref>\"''\u041f\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043c\u043e \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u044f, \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432\u043e \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420, \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u0442 \u043f\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u044b... '''Walther P99'''''\"<br/>\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439. [http://www.bratishka.ru/archiv/2009/6/2009_6_7.php \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044b: \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u00ab\u0410\u043b\u044c\u0444\u0430\u00bb: \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043c \u043d\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0435\u0442] // \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0448\u043a\u0430\", \u0438\u044e\u043d\u044c 2009</ref>\n*{{flag|United Kingdom}}: [[Nottinghamshire Police]] armed specialist units used the P99DAO.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freiwilliger-polizeidienst.de/Infothek/Meinungen_und_Ansichten/Armed_Officers_in_UK/armed_officers_in_uk.html|title=Nottinghamshire Police use P990DAO}}</ref> In 2016 the units switched to the [[Glock#9.C3.9719mm Parabellum|Glock 17]] pistol.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Walther P99-JH02.jpg|P99QA field stripped to its main parts\nImage:WALTHER P99TA.jpg|P99 TA with laser unit and flash suppressor\nFile:Walther P99c AS PICT0024.jpg|Polish made P99c AS\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Walther P22]], a rimfire pistol possessing similar styling and ergonomics chambered in [[.22 LR]].\n*[[Walther PK380]], a centerfire pistol also possessing similar styling and ergonomics with an overall size between the P22 and P99, but chambered in [[.380 ACP]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Walther P99}}\n*[http://www.waltherarms.com/handguns/p99/ P99 Semi-Automatic Pistols] at Carl Walther Sportwaffen GmbH\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100613041019/http://www.carl-walther.de/downloads/Defense-Katalog-2008-DE-EN.pdf Walther 2008 Defense Catalog]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130319063410/http://www.waltherarms.com/resources/manuals/279%2093%2016%20a%20Instruction%20Manual%20P99.pdf P99 Manual]\n*[http://www.waltherarms.com/products/handguns/p99/ Walther Arms P99]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040314102751/http://www.gunfaqs.org/P99FAQ/index.html Walther P99 FAQ \"Lenaburg Edition\"]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111117000919/http://lundestudio.com/WaltherP99FAQ/index.html Ken Lunde's SIG Pro FAQ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100914213257/http://world.guns.ru/handguns/hg14-e.htm Walther P99 at World Guns]\n*[http://www.waltherforums.com/ Walther Forums]\n\n{{Walther}}\n\n[[Category:.40 S&W semi-automatic pistols]]\n[[Category:9\u00d721mm IMI semi-automatic pistols]]\n[[Category:9mm Parabellum semi-automatic pistols]]\n[[Category:Police weapons]]\n[[Category:Post\u2013Cold War weapons of Germany]]\n[[Category:Short recoil firearms]]\n[[Category:Walther semi-automatic pistols|P99]]\n[[Category:Weapons and ammunition introduced in 1996]]\n", "name_user": "TomaHawk61", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduct evolution", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walther_P99"}
{"title_page": "Chakra (JavaScript engine)", "text_new": "{{About|the JavaScript engine used in Microsoft Edge. For the JavaScript engine used in Internet Explorer 9 through 11, see [[Chakra (JScript engine)]]||Chakra (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox Software\n| name                   = Chakra\n| logo                   = \n| screenshot             = \n| caption                = \n| developer              = [[Microsoft]]\n| latest release version = v1.11.18\n| latest release date    = {{Start date and age|2020|04|14}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/microsoft/ChakraCore/tags|title=Tags \u00b7 microsoft/ChakraCore \u00b7 GitHub|website=GitHub ChakraCore repository|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n| size                   = \n| programming language   = [[C++]]\n| operating system       = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[macOS]], [[Linux]]\n| platform               = [[IA-32]], [[x86-64]], [[ARM architecture|ARM]], [[ARM64]]\n| genre                  = [[JavaScript]] engine\n| license                = [[MIT License]]\n| website                = \n}}\n'''Chakra''' is a [[JavaScript]] engine developed by [[Microsoft]] for its [[Microsoft Edge]] [[web browser]]. It is a [[Fork (software development)|fork]] of the [[Chakra (JScript engine)|JScript engine]] used in [[Internet Explorer]]. Like the [[EdgeHTML|Edge layout engine]] and unlike previous versions in [[Internet Explorer]], the declared intention is that it will reflect the \"Living Web\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Targeting Edge vs. Legacy Engines in JsRT APIs|url=https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dn903710(v=vs.94).aspx|accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref> On December 5, 2015, it was announced that core components of ''Chakra'' will be open-sourced as '''ChakraCore'''.\n\n==Standards support==\nChakra supports [[ECMAScript]] 5.1 with partial support for [[ECMAScript]] 6.<ref>{{cite web|title=Microsoft Edge Platform Status|url=https://dev.modern.ie/platform/status//?filter=f0100001c&search=es6|publisher=Microsoft.com|accessdate=10 September 2015}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Open sourcing==\nFollowing an initial announcement on December 5, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.windows.com/msedgedev/2015/12/05/open-source-chakra-core/|title=Microsoft Edge's JavaScript engine to go open-source|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|accessdate=December 8, 2015|date=2015-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\"ChakraCoreopensourced\">[http://www.zdnet.com/article/microsoft-open-sources-its-edge-web-browser-javascript-engine-and-plans-to-port-it-to-linux/ Microsoft open sources Edge web browser's JavaScript engine, plans port to Linux] on [[zdnet.com]] by Steven J. Vaughan-Nichols (on January 13, 2016)</ref> Microsoft open sourced the Chakra engine as ChakraCore, including all the key components of the JavaScript engine powering Microsoft Edge on their GitHub page under the [[MIT License]] on January 13, 2016.<ref name=\"ChakraCoreopensourced\" /><ref>[https://github.com/Microsoft/ChakraCore ChakraCore] on [[github.com]]</ref> ChakraCore is essentially the same as the Chakra engine that powers the [[Microsoft Edge]] browser, but with platform-agnostic bindings, i.e. without the specific interfaces utilised within the [[Universal Windows Platform apps|Universal Windows App]] platform.\n\nMicrosoft has also created a project on [[GitHub]] that allows [[Node.js]] to use ChakraCore as its JavaScript engine instead of [[V8 (JavaScript engine)|V8]].<ref>[https://github.com/Microsoft/node Node.js enabled for ChakraCore] on github.com</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[Microsoft Edge]]\n* [[JavaScript engine]]\n* [[JScript]]\n* [[Chakra (JScript engine)]]\n* [[ECMAScript]]\n* [[List of ECMAScript engines]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{github|https://github.com/microsoft/ChakraCore}}\n\n{{ECMAScript}}\n{{Microsoft}}\n{{Microsoft FOSS}}\n\n[[Category:JavaScript engines]]\n[[Category:Microsoft free software]]\n\n{{Internet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the JavaScript engine used in Microsoft Edge. For the JavaScript engine used in Internet Explorer 9 through 11, see [[Chakra (JScript engine)]]||Chakra (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox Software\n| name                   = Chakra\n| logo                   = \n| screenshot             = \n| caption                = \n| developer              = [[Microsoft]]\n| latest release version = v1.11.17\n| latest release date    = {{Start date and age|2020|03|10}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/microsoft/ChakraCore/tags|title=Tags \u00b7 microsoft/ChakraCore \u00b7 GitHub|website=GitHub ChakraCore repository|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n| size                   = \n| programming language   = [[C++]]\n| operating system       = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[macOS]], [[Linux]]\n| platform               = [[IA-32]], [[x86-64]], [[ARM architecture|ARM]], [[ARM64]]\n| genre                  = [[JavaScript]] engine\n| license                = [[MIT License]]\n| website                = \n}}\n'''Chakra''' is a [[JavaScript]] engine developed by [[Microsoft]] for its [[Microsoft Edge]] [[web browser]]. It is a [[Fork (software development)|fork]] of the [[Chakra (JScript engine)|JScript engine]] used in [[Internet Explorer]]. Like the [[EdgeHTML|Edge layout engine]] and unlike previous versions in [[Internet Explorer]], the declared intention is that it will reflect the \"Living Web\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Targeting Edge vs. Legacy Engines in JsRT APIs|url=https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dn903710(v=vs.94).aspx|accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref> On December 5, 2015, it was announced that core components of ''Chakra'' will be open-sourced as '''ChakraCore'''.\n\n==Standards support==\nChakra supports [[ECMAScript]] 5.1 with partial support for [[ECMAScript]] 6.<ref>{{cite web|title=Microsoft Edge Platform Status|url=https://dev.modern.ie/platform/status//?filter=f0100001c&search=es6|publisher=Microsoft.com|accessdate=10 September 2015}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Open sourcing==\nFollowing an initial announcement on December 5, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.windows.com/msedgedev/2015/12/05/open-source-chakra-core/|title=Microsoft Edge's JavaScript engine to go open-source|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|accessdate=December 8, 2015|date=2015-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\"ChakraCoreopensourced\">[http://www.zdnet.com/article/microsoft-open-sources-its-edge-web-browser-javascript-engine-and-plans-to-port-it-to-linux/ Microsoft open sources Edge web browser's JavaScript engine, plans port to Linux] on [[zdnet.com]] by Steven J. Vaughan-Nichols (on January 13, 2016)</ref> Microsoft open sourced the Chakra engine as ChakraCore, including all the key components of the JavaScript engine powering Microsoft Edge on their GitHub page under the [[MIT License]] on January 13, 2016.<ref name=\"ChakraCoreopensourced\" /><ref>[https://github.com/Microsoft/ChakraCore ChakraCore] on [[github.com]]</ref> ChakraCore is essentially the same as the Chakra engine that powers the [[Microsoft Edge]] browser, but with platform-agnostic bindings, i.e. without the specific interfaces utilised within the [[Universal Windows Platform apps|Universal Windows App]] platform.\n\nMicrosoft has also created a project on [[GitHub]] that allows [[Node.js]] to use ChakraCore as its JavaScript engine instead of [[V8 (JavaScript engine)|V8]].<ref>[https://github.com/Microsoft/node Node.js enabled for ChakraCore] on github.com</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[Microsoft Edge]]\n* [[JavaScript engine]]\n* [[JScript]]\n* [[Chakra (JScript engine)]]\n* [[ECMAScript]]\n* [[List of ECMAScript engines]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{github|https://github.com/microsoft/ChakraCore}}\n\n{{ECMAScript}}\n{{Microsoft}}\n{{Microsoft FOSS}}\n\n[[Category:JavaScript engines]]\n[[Category:Microsoft free software]]\n\n{{Internet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ghettoblaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chakra_(JavaScript_engine)"}
